ang || Samsol Bari Jamali || UMNO || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 59.45\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:brown;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''Safe'''</span>\n|-\n| Johor Lama || Rosleli Jahari || UMNO || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 60.57\n|-\n| Tanjung Surat || Syed Sis Syed A. Rahman || UMNO || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 65.37\n|-\n| Penawar || Sharifah Azizah Syed Zain || UMNO || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 70.35\n|-\n| Sedili || Rasman Ithnain || UMNO || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 75.98\n|}\n{{clear}}\n{{cob}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Malaysian State Assembly Representatives (2013-)|List of State Seats Representatives in Malaysia]]\n* [[State legislative assemblies of Malaysia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Johor State Legislative Assembly}}\n* [http://www.johor.gov.my/ Johor State Government official website]\n\n{{Legislatures of Malaysia}}\n{{Johor}}\n\n[[Category:Johor State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:State legislatures of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Unicameral legislatures]]\n[[Category:Politics of Johor]]\n", "name_user": "Qaidul", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johor_State_Legislative_Assembly"}
{"title_page": "Safavid Georgia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Safavid Georgia\n|native_name = Vel\u0101yat-e Gorjest\u0101n\n|common_name = Gorjestan\n|government_type  = [[Velayat]]\n|life_span    = 1510s \u2013 1736\n|era          = \n|status       = Province of the [[Safavid Iran|Safavid Empire]]\n|p1           = \n|flag_p1      = \n|p2           =\n|flag_p2      = \n|s1           = Afsharid dynasty\n|flag_s1      = Nader_Shah_Flag.svg\n|s2           = \n|flag_s2      = \n|image_coat   = \n|image_flag   = \n|image_map    = Northwestern part of the Safavid Empire (cropped, v2).png\n|image_map_caption  = Northwestern part of the Safavid Empire\n|national_motto   = \n|national_anthem  = \n|capital          = [[Tiflis]] (Tbilisi)\n|common_languages = [[Georgian language|Georgian]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]]\n|currency         = \n|title_leader = \n|leader1      = \n|leader2      = \n|title_deputy = \n|deputy1      = \n|deputy2      = \n|stat_area3 = \n|stat_pop1 =\n|today={{flag|Armenia}}<br>{{flag|Azerbaijan}}<br>{{flag|Georgia}}<br>{{flag|Russia}}\n}}\nThe '''province of Georgia''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0648\u0644\u0627\u06cc\u062a \u06af\u0631\u062c\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646|translit=Vel\u0101yat-e Gorjest\u0101n}}) was a ''[[vilayat|velayat]]'' (province) of the [[Safavid Empire]] located in the area of present-day [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=17\u201318}} The territory of the province was principally made up of the two subordinate eastern Georgian kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Kartli|Kartli]] ({{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0627\u0631\u062a\u0644\u06cc|translit=Kartil}}) and [[Kingdom of Kakheti|Kakheti]] ({{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0627\u062e\u062a\u06cc|translit=Kakhet}}) and, briefly, parts of the [[Samtskhe\u2013Saatabago|Principality of Samtskhe]].{{efn|Eastern Samtskhe was part of the Safavid Empire from 1551 to 1582, as well as for several years after 1613.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=85}}}} The city of [[Tbilisi|Tiflis]] (present-day Tbilisi) was its administrative center, the base of Safavid power in the province, and the seat of the rulers of Kartli. It also housed an important Safavid [[Mint (facility)|mint]].\n\nSafavid rule was mainly exercised through the approval or appointment of Georgian royals of the [[Bagrationi dynasty]], at times converts to [[Shia Islam]], as ''[[W\u0101li|valis]]'' or ''[[Khan (title)|khan]]s''.{{efn|Before [[Abbas I of Persia|Abbas I]]'s reign (1588\u20131629), governors of Georgia were usually referred to as ''hakem''.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=83}} Sometimes they were also styled as ''[[sultan|soltan]] (salatin)''.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=86}}}} The eastern Georgian kingdoms had been subjected in the early 16th century, their rulers did not commonly convert. Tiflis was garrisoned by an Iranian force as early as Ismail{{nbsp}}I's reign, but relations between the Georgians and Safavids at the time mostly bore features of traditional [[vassalage]]. [[David XI of Kartli|Davud Khan]] (David XI) was the first Safavid-appointed ruler, whose placement on the throne of Kartli in 1562 marked the start of nearly two and a half centuries of [[Iran]]ian political control of eastern Georgia. During the same period, [[Culture of Iran|Iranian cultural]] influence dominated eastern Georgia.\n\nFrom [[Tahmasp I]]'s reign onwards ({{reign|1524|1576}}), the province was of great strategic importance. Many ethnic [[Georgians]], generally from Kartli and Kakheti, rose to prominence in the Safavid state. These men held many of the highest positions in the civil and military administration, and many women entered the harem of the ruling class. By the late Safavid period, Georgians formed the mainstay of the Safavid army as well. The establishment of a large [[Iranian Georgians|Georgian community in Iran]] proper dates back to the era of Safavid suzerainty in Georgia. As the province was a border entity, the ''valis'' of Georgia exercised more autonomy than other provinces of the Safavid empire; it could therefore be compared to the Arabestan Province (present-day [[Khuzestan Province]]), in the southwestern part of the empire.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=17\u201318}} The province of Georgia was one of only four Safavid administrative territories where governors were consistently given the title of ''vali''.\n\n==History==\n{{History of Georgia (country)}}\n\n===16th century===\nThe first [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid]] king (''[[shah]]'') [[Ismail I]] ({{Reign}}1501\u20131524) made the two kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Kartli|Kartli]] and [[Kingdom of Kakheti|Kakheti]] his [[Vassal state|vassals]] as early as the 1510s.{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|pages=164, 166}} However, distracted by the task of establishing power in [[Iran]], he did not tighten his hold on [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]. He did raid Georgia a number of times, notably in 1518, which reconfirmed its status as a vassal, and in 1522, which resulted in Tiflis being garrisoned by a large Safavid force, but it was only under his son and successor [[Tahmasp I]] (r.{{nbsp}}1524\u20131576) that a genuine province with Safavid-appointed rulers and governors began to take shape.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=166}}\n\nTahmasp I undertook active steps to integrate Georgia into the Safavid domains. His four campaigns against [[Luarsab I of Kartli]] (1540\u20131541, 1546\u20131547, 1551, and 1553\u20131554) resulted in the re-occupation of Kartli, and a Safavid force was permanently stationed in [[Tiflis]] in 1551.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}{{sfn|Floor|2008|pages=295\u2013296}} A key outcome of these campaigns, apart from cementing Safavid hold in central-eastern Georgia, was that they brought to Iran proper (hereafter, simply \"Iran\") large numbers of Georgian prisoners of war.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} Beyond this, the sons of notable Georgians were frequently brought up at the shah's court as part of their tributary relationship with the Safavids.{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=28}} Beginning with the rule of Tahmasp{{nbsp}}I, Georgians would contribute greatly to the character of Safavid society and play a major role in its army and civil administration.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} This newly introduced ethnic element in the Safavid state would later be known in historiography as the \"third force\" alongside the two \"founding elements\" of the Safavid state, the Persians and the Turkomans.{{efn|The \"third force\" included the [[Circassians]] and [[Armenians]].}} \n[[File:Safavid_Courtiers_Leading_Georgian_Captives_(The_Metropolitan_Museum_of_Art).jpg|thumb|150px|right|Safavid courtiers leading Georgian captives. A mid-16th century Persian textile panel from the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].]]\nIn 1551 the Safavids gained the eastern part of the [[Samtskhe\u2013Saatabago|principality of Samtskhe]].{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=173}}{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=85}} In 1555, during Tahmasp{{nbsp}}I's reign, the [[Peace of Amasya]] was signed with the neighboring [[Ottoman Empire]]. According to the terms of the treaty, eastern Georgia (including eastern Samtskhe) remained in Iranian hands while western Georgia (including western Samtskhe) ended up in Turkish hands.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=xxxi}} To speed up the process of integration into the empire, Tahmasp{{nbsp}}I imposed numerous Iranian political and social institutions such as bilingual Georgian\u2013Persian ''[[Firman|farm\u00e2ns]]'', with the aim of establishing Persian as the official administrative language of Safavid Georgia.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} It was also during his reign that the first Georgian royal, a convert to Islam named [[Daud Khan of Kartli|Davud Khan]] (1569\u20131578) was put on the puppet throne in Tiflis.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} These events marked the start of almost 250 years of Iranian political dominance, with a few brief intermissions, over eastern Georgia.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=48}}\n\nIn 1559, the first provincial [[vizier]] was assigned to the [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]] province, with authority over the Georgia province as well as [[Safavid Shirvan|Shirvan]] including [[Shaki, Azerbaijan|Shakki]].{{sfn|Floor|2001|pages=108-109}} These provincial viziers, also known as royal viziers, held the title of ''vazir-e koll'', and received instructions from the central government located in the royal capital, instead of the local governor.{{sfn|Floor|2001|pages=108-109}} Challenging the Safavid possession of eastern Caucasus, the Ottomans invaded the Georgian polities [[Lala Mustafa Pasha's Caucasian campaign|in a victorious campaign]] in 1578. As a result, the Safavids released the Georgian rebel ruler [[Simon I of Kartli|Shahnavaz Khan]] (Simon{{nbsp}}I of Kartli) from captivity to enable him to join the fight against the Ottomans.{{efn|Simon I was earlier known for his fierce resistance against the Safavid domination, which resulted in his being imprisoned for several years at the [[Alamut Castle]].}} Though Simon achieved considerable success in Kartli, he was eventually captured by the Ottoman troops and died in captivity in Constantinople.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} In the period 1580\u20131581 the Safavid government sent a force accompanied by the ''[[tupchi-bashi]]'' Morad Khan to Georgia together with a number of cannon founders and the materials needed for casting cannon.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=233}} By 1582 the Ottomans were in control of the eastern, Safavid portion of Samtskhe.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=85}} Unable to resist the Ottoman invasion, [[Manuchar II Jaqeli]] of Samtskhe accepted the Iranian overlordship as well and moved to the Safavid court, where he lived until his death in 1614.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} By the [[Treaty of Constantinople (1590)|Treaty of Constantinople]] in 1590, the Safavids lost control over Georgia as they were forced to recognize the whole province as an Ottoman possession.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}\n\n===17th century===\n\n[[File:\u10e0\u10dd\u10e1\u10e2\u10dd\u10db_\u10ee\u10d0\u10dc\u10d8.gif|thumb|150px|left|[[Rostom of Kartli|Rostam Khan]] (Rostom), ''vali'' of Kartli, eastern Georgia, 1633\u20131658]]\nAt the beginning of the rule of [[Abbas I of Persia|Abbas I]], the importance of Georgia and the influence of ethnic Georgians in the Safavid state increased and they came to be known as the \"third force\". Already by 1595 an ethnic Georgian from Kartli, [[Allahverdi Khan]], originally surnamed [[Undiladze]], had become one of the most powerful figures in the Safavid state.{{sfn|Savory|2007|page=81}} By the end of the 16th{{nbsp}}century, Georgians, forming an increasingly influential military faction, became a major threat to the [[Qizilbash]], the traditional backbone of the Safavid army.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} At the same time, the Georgians at the Safavid court vied for influence among each other as well as against their [[Circassians|Circassian]] counterparts.{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=17}} By and large, Abbas{{nbsp}}I's policy towards the province can be seen as a continuing the previous efforts to fully integrate the area in the Safavid Empire.\n\nIn the early years of the 17th century, Abbas re-established Safavid influence in eastern Georgia. There was a resistance in Kakheti in 1605, when the rebels overthrew pro-Iranian patricide [[Constantine I of Kakheti|Constantine Khan]] and Abbas{{nbsp}}I acceded to their demands to approve [[Teimuraz I of Kakheti|Tahmuras Khan]] (Teimuraz{{nbsp}}I) as the new king of Kakheti.{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=50}}{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} At the same time, he also confirmed [[Luarsab II of Kartli|Lohrasb]] (Luarsab{{nbsp}}II) as ''vali'' of Kartli. However, when Lohrasb started to work against Safavid interests and refused to convert to Islam, Abbas{{nbsp}}I had him incarcerated in [[Astarabad]] and later executed in [[Shiraz]].{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}\n\nIn 1607 Abbas appointed [[Manuchar III Jaqeli]] as ruler of (eastern) Samtskhe.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} By 1613\u20131614 Abbas had restored Safavid control over eastern Samtskhe.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=85}} In 1614\u20131617, as a punishment for disobedience shown by his formerly loyal subjects Lohrasb and Tahmuras Khan, Abbas{{nbsp}}I launched several [[Abbas I's Kakhetian and Kartlian campaigns|major punitive campaigns]] in his Georgian territories. These campaigns resulted in the sack of [[Tiflis]], the ravaging of the entire area, the massacre of many tens of thousands, and the deportation of hundreds of thousands of ethnic Georgians to Iran.{{sfn|Blow|2009|page=174}}{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pages=291, 536}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=191}} These deportees further augmented the [[Iranian Georgians|Georgian community in Iran]].{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=536}} In the meantime, Abbas{{nbsp}}I appointed [[Bagrat VII of Kartli|Bagrat Khan]] as governor of Kartli, and [[Bektash of Kakheti|Bektash Beg Torkman]] as governor of Kakheti.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=164}} In 1619 Abbas{{nbsp}}I appointed Bagrat's son [[Simon II of Kartli|Semayun Khan]], a loyalist born and raised in [[Isfahan]], as khan, or ''vali'', of Kartli, and appointed another non-royal Safavid official as governor of Kakheti, in order to maintain a tight grip on this part of the province.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=600}} He also moved many Qizilbash tribal folk to the Georgia province in order to strengthen central control.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=145}} From the mid-1610s onwards, Kakheti was often under the direct governorship of [[Qizilbash]] lords.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=86}}\n\nAround 1620 Abbas relocated some 8,000 [[History of the Jews in Georgia|Jews]] from the province, along with 40,000 Armenians, to the newly built city of [[Farahabad, Mazandaran|Farahabad]].{{sfn|Matthee|1999|page=44}} In these years, he moved a total of about 15,000 families from the [[Caucasus]] to [[Mazandaran Province|Mazandaran]].{{sfn|Blow|2009|page=105}}{{efn|Amongst the deportees there were also Muslims from Georgia, and sections of the [[Safavid Shirvan|Shirvan]] and [[Safavid Qarabagh|Karabakh]] population.}}\nIn 1624\u201325 Manuchar III Jaqeli, appointed earlier by Abbas{{nbsp}}I as nominal ruler of Samtskhe, moved to Kartli to join the rebellion of [[Giorgi Saakadze|Murav-Beg]] (Giorgi Saakadze) against Safavid rule.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pages=194, 379}} Some time later, while away from Samtskhe, he decided to accept Ottoman suzerainty.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pages=194, 379}} However, when he returned to Samtskhe in 1625 for negotiations in the western (Ottoman) part of Samtskhe, he was killed by his own uncle.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pages=194, 379}} Subsequently, the Ottomans incorporated the western part of Samtskhe as a [[Eyalet|pashalik]].{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=52}} The Safavids retained control of the eastern part.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=140}} The remaining century of Safavid rule in Georgia, after Abbas{{nbsp}}I's death in 1629, was marked by unprecedented Iranian influence.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} Under the ''vali'' [[Rostom of Kartli|Khosrow Mirza]], Safavid Georgia saw a period of relative peace and prosperity. In return for his loyalty, the then-incumbent king, [[Safi of Persia|Safi]] ({{reign|1629|1642}}), had given him the title of Rostam Khan, and had made him governor of Kartli, a post which he held for more than twenty years. Kakheti however, came under direct Safavid rule.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}\n\nRostam Khan was a childless [[widower]], however, and thus needed a wife and offspring. Being the loyal servant he was, after consulting the Safavid king, Rostam was allowed to marry a sister of [[Levan II Dadiani]], [[Principality of Mingrelia|ruler of Mingrelia]] (western Georgia), named [[Mariam Dadiani|Mariam]].{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} The marriage fit well with the political ambitions of the Safavid state and of Rostam himself.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} Not only would this alliance with the Dadiani, i.e. Mingrelia, give Rostam an ally against Tahmuras Khan (Teimuraz{{nbsp}}I) and [[George III of Imereti]], but it would also provide Rostam with a line of successors who would be as loyal to the Safavid crown as he was.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} Also important was the fact that it would enhance Safavid plans to conquer [[Kingdom of Imereti|Imereti]].{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} It would create a perfect circumstance if a campaign was needed against the Ottomans, with whom they [[Ottoman\u2013Safavid War (1623\u201339)|were at war at the time]] over Imereti.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} King Safi paid for the wedding gifts, and sent some 50,000 ''marchil'', roughly half a ton of silver, to the ruler of Mingrelia, and provided him with an annual salary of 1,000 ''[[Iranian toman|tomans]]'' (3-gram gold coins); an alliance was thus founded with the Mingrelians.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} The marriage preparations alarmed the Imeretians. The groom's party was a 30,000-strong army marching to meet Levan's heavily armed entourage. George{{nbsp}}III of Imereti blocked the border with Kartli, compelling Rostom's wedding party to take a circuitous route via [[Akhaltsikhe]], and intercepted Dadiani on his way to the marriage, but he was defeated and taken prisoner by Levan at the Kaka Bridge near [[Baghdati]].{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}}\n\nIn 1639, by the [[Treaty of Zuhab]] which ended the 1623\u20131639 war, the Caucasus was decisively partitioned between the Safavids and Ottomans roughly along the lines of the earlier Amasya treaty of 1555. Kartli and Kakheti were reconfirmed as Iranian domains, while everything to the west of it remained in Ottoman hands. Samtskhe\u2013Meskheti, including its eastern part, was irrevocably lost.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=85}}\n\nIn 1654, during the reign of King [[Abbas II of Persia|Abbas II]] ({{reign|1642|1666}}), Kartli was turned into crown land (''khasseh''), and therefore subjected to direct Safavid taxation.{{sfn|Barendse|2002|page=209}}{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=309}} The amount of land directly taxed by the state reached its greatest extent in this year.{{sfn|Barendse|2002|page=209}} Also during Abbas{{nbsp}}II's reign, an earlier plan was revived to populate the eastern part of the province, Kakheti, with Turkic nomads. This measure incited [[Bakhtrioni Uprising|a general uprising]] in 1659. The rebels succeeded in expelling the nomads, but still had to accept the Safavid kings's suzerainty.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} In 1675 a wall was built around Tiflis by king [[Suleiman I of Persia|Suleiman I]] (1666\u20131694).{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=211}} By the 1690s ethnic [[Georgians]] formed the mainstay of the Safavid army.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=114}}\n\n===18th century===\n\nIn 1701 one of the artillerymen (''tupchis'') in Tiflis was appointed ''vakil'' (\"regent\") of the ''[[tupchi-bashi]]'' of Tiflis fortress.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=198}} [[David II of Kakheti|Emamqoli Khan]] (David{{nbsp}}II), born and raised in [[Isfahan]], and known for his loyal service to his Safavid overlords, was made governor of Kakheti in 1703\u20131709 by [[Sultan Husayn]] ({{reign|1694|1722}}) due to his father, [[Heraclius I of Kakheti|Nazar-Ali Khan]] (Heraclius{{nbsp}}I), being stationed at Isfahan during the entire period.\n\n[[File:1708._\u10d3\u10d0\u10d5\u10d8\u10d7_II-\u10e1_\u10ec\u10e7\u10d0\u10da\u10dd\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1_\u10d2\u10d0\u10dc\u10d0\u10ee\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1_\u10e1\u10d8\u10d2\u10d4\u10da\u10d8.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[David II of Kakheti|Emamqoli Khan]] (David{{nbsp}}II of Kakheti)]]\nIn 1709, following his father's death, he was formally appointed as the new governor of Kakheti. However, until 1715, he served as ''vali in absentia'' due to his being obliged to stay at the court in Isfahan.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=249}} To the west, in Kartli, the administration was given to two successive governors who both served as ''vali in absentia'' due to being stationed in other parts of the empire: [[George XI of Kartli|Shah-Navaz Khan II, Gorgin Khan]] (George XI); and [[Kaikhosro of Kartli|Kaykhosrow Khan]]. Due to this, in the years 1703\u20131714, the administration there was led by two successive regents (''janeshins'') namely [[Levan of Kartli|Shah-Qoli Khan]] (Levan) and [[Vakhtang VI of Kartli|Hosayn-Qoli Khan]] (Vakhtang{{nbsp}}VI).\n\nIn 1712\u20131719 Hosayn-Qoli Khan was forced to stay in Iran, and the Safavid king therefore gave the governorships of Kartli to others, amongst them [[Jesse of Kartli|Ali-Qoli Khan]] (Jesse) and ''janeshins'' such as [[Prince Bakar of Kartli|Shah-Navaz, Bakar Mirza]]. In 1719 the Iranian government decided to send Hosayn-Qoli Khan, who had occupied several other high positions since 1716, back to Georgia with the task of handling the Lezgin rebellion.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=225}} Assisted by the ruler of neighboring Kakheti, as well as the governor (''beglarbeg'') of [[Safavid Shirvan|Shirvan]], Hosayn-Qoli made significant progress in putting a halt to the Lezgins.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=225}} However, in the winter of 1721, at a crucial moment in the campaign, he was recalled.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=225}} The order, which came after the fall of grand vizier [[Fath-Ali Khan Daghestani]], was made at the instigation of the eunuch faction within the royal court, who had persuaded the shah that a successful end to the campaign would do the Safavid realm more harm than good. In their view, it would enable Vakhtang, the Safavid ''[[Vali (governor)|vali]]'', to form an alliance with Russia with an eye to conquering Iran.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=225}} Shortly after, the Lezgins overran [[Safavid Shirvan|Shirvan]], whereafter they [[Sack of Shamakhi (1721)|sacked and looted]] the provincial capital of [[Shamakhi]] and massacred much of its population. In 1722 Emamqoli Khan died and was buried in [[Qom, Iran|Qom]]. Sultan Husayn then appointed his brother [[Constantine II of Kakheti|Mahmad Qoli Khan]] (Constantine{{nbsp}}II) as the new governor of Kakheti.\n\nWhen the capital of Isfahan was put under [[Siege of Isfahan|siege in 1722]], Hosayn-Qoli Khan defied the royal orders and refused to send the requested relief force.{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=54}} In the meantime, Russia took full advantage of the situation. With the Safavids on the brink of collapse, they launched a campaign in 1722\u20131723 that resulted in the [[Russo-Persian War (1722\u20131723)|annexation of the coastal territories]]. The Ottomans, also taking advantage of the situation, overran the province of Georgia and other territories to the west of the area that the Russians had captured.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=142}} By the [[Treaty of Constantinople (1724)|Treaty of Constantinople]], the two powers further divided the annexed territories between them, with the Ottomans again retaining Georgia.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|pages=226\u2013227}} The rebellious Hosayn-Qoli Khan, who had sided with the Russians during their invasion in 1722\u20131723, in what turned out to be an ill-fated alliance, died in exile in Russia in 1737. When the Safavids were restored by [[Nader Shah|Nader Qoli Beg]] (later known as Nader Shah), the ''[[de facto]]'' ruler of Iran, he restored Iranian dominance in the Caucasus and made [[Teimuraz II of Kakheti|Teimuraz II]] ''vali'' of Kakheti, while appointing an Iranian as the governor of Kartli.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} In 1736 Nader deposed the Safavids and became king himself, establishing the [[Afsharid dynasty]].\n\n==Mint==\n[[File:Eight Safavid abbasis struck at the Tiflis mint.jpg|thumb|right|Silver ''abbasis'' minted in Tiflis during the reign of Sultan Husayn ({{Reign|1694|1722}}), with minting dates varying from 1717\u20131718 to 1719\u20131720.]]\n[[File:Safavid shahis struck at the Tiflis mint.jpg|thumb|right|Silver ''panj shahis'' minted in Tiflis in 1716\u20131717 during the reign of Sultan Husayn.]]\n{{see also|Abbasi (currency)|Georgian abazi}}\nOne of the most important Safavid [[Mint (facility)|mint]]s was located in the province of Georgia, in Tiflis. Close to the border with the Ottoman Empire, the Tiflis mint was important to the Safavids, for [[bullion]] (i.e. silver bars, Spanish [[Spanish real|reals]], Dutch [[rijksdaalder]]s) for the minting of coins was largely imported from and through the Ottoman Empire (and Russia).{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=68}}{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=53}} Upon arrival in Iran, the bullion was always brought to Tiflis, Erivan, or Tabriz to be melted into Iranian coins.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=5, 15}} Tiflis was thus a major stopping point for merchants who returned with silver.{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=68}} It was also one of the few mints, alongside the ones at Tabriz and [[Yerevan|Erivan]] (Yerevan), where re-minting took place.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=53}} In the 17th century the Tiflis mint was one of the most active Safavid mints.{{sfn|Barendse|2002|page=221}}\n\nThe Tiflis mint also lay on a route widely used by silk traders.{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=68}} According to French traveller [[Jean Baptiste Tavernier]], traders who went to Gilan to negotiate over silk, went to the mint at Tiflis, for the mint master (''zarrab-bashi'') gave a 2%{{nbsp}}discount on silver for silk traders.{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=68}} Tavernier notes that this is partly due to the silver coins from Tiflis being a little less [[Fineness|fine]].{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|pages=68\u201369}}\n\nThe coins minted at Tiflis were mostly used for the local citizens, rather than for the local Safavid garrison.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=17}} The coins always had to bear the Safavid rulers' name and follow the Safavid types, legends, and weight standards.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=17\u201318}} In many other regards, however, the appointed ''valis'' were granted a great deal of autonomy in terms of minting practises.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=17\u201318}} For example, the ''vali'' reportedly was allowed to benefit from the profit accrued by the mints in the province.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=17}}\n\nDuring the reign of Suleiman I, the economic situation worsened.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=130\u2013131}} The amount of precious metal coming into the country decreased, and as a result the quality of the coins diminished.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=130\u2013131}} This deficiency in weight was also apparent in coins from the Tiflis mint; in 1688, the ''abbasis'' and ''mahmudis'' struck at the mint were 22.5% below the standard weight they were supposed to have.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=131}} The royal treasury was aware of the issue, and subsequently stopped accepting ''mahmudis'' that had been minted in Tiflis.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=131}}\n\nIn the years 1682\u20131685 the only Safavid mints that were recorded as active were the ones at Tiflis and [[Tabriz]].{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=119}} According to a 1687 report, money played close to no role in Georgia.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=44}} French botanist [[Joseph Pitton de Tournefort]] confirms this: according to his texts of 1701, people in large parts of Georgia preferred to be paid in materials such as bracelets, rings, necklaces, and so forth.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=44}}\n\n==Stationed military force==\nThe province of Georgia hosted many Safavid soldiers, as it was considered a territory of the utmost importance. At the same time, it was a province that bordered the Ottoman Empire.{{sfn|Floor|2001|pages=82\u201383}} A Safavid force was permanently stationed in Tiflis from 1551 onwards.{{sfn|Floor|2008|pages=295\u2013296}} According to [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] reports, some 4,000 Safavid cavalry were stationed in Georgia and [[Ganja, Azerbaijan|Ganja]] in the 1570s.{{sfn|Floor|2001|pages=135\u2013136}} According to traveller [[Jean Chardin]], towards the end of Abbas{{nbsp}}I's reign many troops were stationed in Georgia, of which some 5,000 were \"battle-experienced and trained\".{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=207}} In the mid-17th century, during the reign of [[Abbas II of Persia|Abbas II]] (1642\u20131666), some 50,000 Safavid troops were stationed in the province according to Chardin's figures.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=145}} The French missionary and traveller P\u00e8re Sanson, who was in the Safavid Empire during the latter part of King [[Suleiman I of Persia|Suleiman I]]'s reign (1666\u20131694), wrote that a \"large number\" of troops were stationed in Georgia.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=212}} Towards the end of Sultan Husayn's reign (1694\u20131722), the troops at the behest of the then-governor of Kartli, [[Vakhtang VI of Kartli|Hosayn-Qoli Khan]] (Vakhtang{{nbsp}}VI), numbered some 10,000 [[Georgians]] and 3,000\u20134,000 [[Iranian peoples|Iranians]].{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=225}}\n\nThe ''vali'' of Georgia had a corps of ''[[Qurchi (royal bodyguard)|qurchis]]'' at his disposal, including a ''[[qurchi-bashi]]'', and a legion of specialized qurchis for his \"[[accoutrements]]\" (i.e. ''qurchi-e zereh'', ''qurchi-e kafsh'', ''qurchi-e tarkesh'', etc.).{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=149}} They also had the institution of ''vakil'' (\"regent\"), who could take care of all matters in case it was needed.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=7}}{{efn|The ''vakil'' sometimes also functioned as a tutor (''[[Lala (title)|laleh]]''), in cases when the governor was young.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=7}}}}\n\n==Silk and wine production==\nAlthough the province contributed to the overall [[silk]] production, its silk was said, together with that of [[Karabakh Beylarbeylik|Karabakh\u2013Ganja]], to be of lesser quality than that of [[Gilan Province|Gilan]] and [[Mazandaran Province|Mazandaran]].{{sfn|Matthee|1999|page=37}} Following [[Abbas I of Persia|Abbas I]]'s (1588\u20131629) decisive subduing of Georgia, he ordered that the province should produce more silk in the future.{{sfn|Matthee|1999|page=41}} According to Nicolaas Jacobus Overschie, a [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] representative in the Safavid Empire, of the 2,800 bales of silk that had been produced in 1636, the provinces of Georgia and Karabakh\u2013Ganja had yielded a total of 300 bales.{{sfn|Matthee|1999|page=41}}\n\nAccording to Jean Chardin, the wines produced in Georgia and Shiraz were of excellent quality.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=44}} Every six months the province of Georgia supplied the royal [[wine cellars]] of the Safavid court with some three hundred liters of wine, as part of the total amount of taxes it paid.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|pages=43\u201344}} The governors were responsible for the supervision of the [[viticulture]] of their province.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=44}}\n\n==Cultural influences==\n===Georgian culture===\nFrom the 16th century there was an increase of Iranian influence in Georgian culture.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}} The genres in which it was most apparent were [[Georgian literature|literature]], painting, and [[Georgian architecture|architecture]].{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}} During the Safavid period, many Georgian rulers, princes, and nobles had spent time in Iran. Therefore, Iranian traditions also spread throughout Georgia.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}} The placement of [[David XI of Kartli|Davud Khan]] (David XI) on the puppet throne of Kartli in 1562 did not just initiate a lengthy period of Iranian political dominance; in the same two and a half centuries that followed, until the [[Georgia within the Russian Empire|coming]] of the [[Russian Empire|Russians]] in the 19th century, [[Culture of Iran|Iranian cultural]] influence dominated eastern Georgia (Kartli\u2013Kakheti).{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=48}} According to Jean Chardin, who was in Georgia in 1672, the Georgians followed Iranian traditions.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}} Chardin assumed that the process had been influenced by those nobles who had converted to Islam (in order to obtain positions as state officials), as well as those who encouraged their female relatives to become ladies at court.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}\n\nIn the Safavid period, \"a great number of books\" were translated from Persian into Georgian. The ''Rostomiani'', the Georgian version of the ''[[Shahnameh]]'', was further developed and improved, as well as ''[[Visramiani]]'', the Georgian version of ''[[Vis o Ramin]]''.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}} According to a letter sent to the Pope by a Catholic missionary who [[Floruit|flourished]] in the 17th century, Padre Bernardi, it was to his \"great regret\" that literate Georgians preferred to read works such as the ''Rostomiani'' (''[[Shahnameh]]''), ''Bezhaniani'', and ''Baramguriani'' and were less interested in religious texts.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}}\n\n[[Teimuraz I of Kakheti]] (Tahmuras Khan) is perhaps mostly remembered for creating issues for the central government, but he was fluent in Persian and fond of Persian poetry, which he \"highly valued\".{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} In his words:{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}}\n\n{{quote|The sweetness of Persian speech urged me to compose the music of verse.}}\n\nTeimuraz wrote several poems influenced by the contemporary Persian tradition, packed with \"Persian imagery and allusions, loanwords, and phraseology\". A later Georgian ruler, Vakhtang{{nbsp}}VI (Hosayn-Qoli Khan), was also important in this regard.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} When he was forced to stay in Iran, he learned to excel in Persian. He later used this skill to translate works into Georgian.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} He created a Georgian version of the Persian ''[[Qabus-Nama|Qabusnameh]]'' known as ''Amirnasariani'' (\"The story of Amirnasar\", Amirnasar being the mythical Iranian king [[Kaykavus]]). During his detention in Iran, Vakhtang also translated into Georgian Kashefi's ''[[Panchatantra|Kal\u012bleh o Demneh]]''.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} Later, back in Georgia, he ordered the entire story to be translated once more, while his tutor, [[Sulkhan-Saba Orbeliani]], also made a revised version of Vakhtang's own translation.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} Though Vakhtang, individually, was heavily involved in further developing Georgian-Iranian literary ties (in other words, by his own writings), he also founded an entire school dedicated to translators from Persian into Georgian.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} During this period, a number of folk stories (i.e. ''[[dastan]]s'') that were extremely popular in Iran, were translated into Georgian on his orders.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} One of these was the ''Bakhtiarnameh'', a collection of several novellas, as well as the ''Baramgulandamiani'' (\"Bahram o Golandam\"), originally written by Katebi Nishapuri. The many other Persian-Georgian literary efforts of this era include translations of the [[Quran|Qur'an]] and books on Shia [[jurisprudence]].{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}}{{sfn|Giunashvili|2016}}\n\n===Iranian culture===\nIn another, perhaps unorthodox, way Georgia also influenced the culture of Iran. According to a story, an ethnic Georgian named Scedan Cilaze was so renowned for being able to \"hold\" his liquor, that Safavid King [[Safi of Persia|Safi]] ({{reign|1629|1642}}) invited him to the court in order to hold a drinking competition.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}} After beating everyone at court, the king himself challenged Cilaze, and reportedly died doing so. Though Prof. Matthee reports that the story may be \"apocryphal\", as alcoholism did kill Safi, but not in relation to a drinking contest, it does show that Georgian habits had spread to Iran.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}}\n\nIn the Safavid period, large numbers of ethnic Georgian men entered Safavid government service, whereas many Georgian women entered the harems of the ruling elite and the royal court.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}} Drinking alcohol, a prominent Georgian habits, influenced Iranian society, and more importantly, court culture, during this period.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}} It is especially evident in the taxes the province had to pay{{snd}}they included many liters of wine. The royal harem, the private area of the royal court, was where Safavid rulers grew up; after Abbas{{nbsp}}I's reign, all Safavid rulers grew up there surrounded by mostly Georgian women.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}} There were also many ''[[Military of the Safavid dynasty#Gholam|gholams]]'' who drank. Matthee therefore suggests that it is quite likely that the \"fondness\" for wine exhibited by Safavid rulers originated in this environment.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of rulers of Safavid Georgia]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last1=Babaie|first1=Sussan|last2=Babayan|first2=Kathryn|last3=Baghdiantz-McCabe|first3=Ina|last4=Farhad|first4=Massumeh|title=Slaves of the Shah: New Elites of Safavid Iran|date=2004|publisher=I.B.Tauris|pages=1\u2013256|isbn=978-0857716866|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Barendse|first1=R.J.|title=The Arabian Seas: The Indian Ocean World of the Seventeenth Century|date=2002|location=Armonk, N.Y.|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0765633644|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Blow | first = David | title = Shah Abbas: The Ruthless King Who became an Iranian Legend | year = 2009 | isbn = 978-1845119898 | publisher = I.B.Tauris | location = London, UK | lccn = 2009464064 | url = https://books.google.dk/books?id=K_kBAwAAQBAJ&pg= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Floor|first1=Willem|authorlink=Willem Floor|title=Safavid Government Institutions|date=2001|publisher=Mazda Publishers|location=Costa Mesa, California|isbn=978-1568591353|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Floor|first1=Willem|title=Titles and Emoluments in Safavid Iran: A Third Manual of Safavid Administration, by Mirza Naqi Nasiri|date=2008|publisher=Mage Publishers|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=978-1933823232|pages=1\u2013324|ref = harv}} \n* {{cite book|last=Gelashvili|first=Nana|chapter=Iranian-Georgian relations during the Reign of Rostom (1633-58)|title=Iran and the World in the Safavid Age|publisher=I.B.Tauris|location=London|year=2012|isbn=978-1780769905|ref=harv| editor-given1 = Willem | editor-surname1 = Floor | editor-given2 = Edmund | editor-surname2 = Herzig | editor-link2 = Edmund Herzig | postscript = .}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | title = Gorgijanidze, Parsadan | last = Giunashvili | first = Jemshid | authorlink = Jamshid Giunashvili | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/gorgijanidze-parsadan | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica | pages =  | location = | publisher = | year = 2016 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | title = Georgia iv. Literary contacts with Persia | last = Gvakharia | first = Aleksandre | authorlink = | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/georgia-iv--1 | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica, Vol. X, Fasc. 5 | pages = 481\u2013486 | location = | publisher = | year = 2001 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | title = Georgia ii. History of Iranian-Georgian Relations | last = Hitchins | first = Keith | authorlink = | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/georgia-ii-history- | editor-last = | editor-first = | editor-link = | encyclopedia = Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica, Vol. X, Fasc. 4 | pages = 464\u2013470 | location = | publisher = | year = 2001 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Matthee|first1=Rudolph P.|title=The Politics of Trade in Safavid Iran: Silk for Silver, 1600\u20131730|date=1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-64131-9|page=120|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=5U0yECMV--wC&dq=qazaq+khan+cherkes&hl=nl&source=gbs_navlinks_s|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Matthee|first1=Rudolph P.|title=The Pursuit of Pleasure: Drugs and Stimulants in Iranian History, 1500-1900|date=2005|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton, New Jersey|isbn=978-0691118550|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Matthee|first1=Rudi|title=Persia in Crisis: Safavid Decline and the Fall of Isfahan|date=2012|publisher=I.B.Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1-84511-745-0|url=|pages=1\u2013371|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Matthee|first1=Rudi|last2=Floor|first2=Willem|last3=Clawson|first3=Patrick|title=The Monetary History of Iran: From the Safavids to the Qajars|date=2013|publisher=I.B.Tauris|location=London; New York|isbn=978-0857721723|pages=1\u2013320|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Mikaberidze|first1=Alexander|authorlink=Alexander Mikaberidze|title=Historical Dictionary of Georgia|date=2015|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=9781442241466|edition=2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Rayfield|first1=Donald|authorlink=Donald Rayfield|title=Edge of Empires: A History of Georgia|date=2012|publisher=Reaktion Books|location=London|isbn=978-1780230702|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Savory|first1=Roger|authorlink1=Roger Savory|title=Iran Under the Safavids|date=2007|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0521042512|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Suny|first1=Ronald Grigor|authorlink1=Ronald Grigor Suny|title=The Making of the Georgian Nation|date=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington, Indiana|isbn=978-0253209153|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last1=Floor|first1=Willem|last2=Faghfoory|first2=Mohammad H.|title=The Dastur Al-moluk: A Safavid State Manual, by  Mohammad Rafi' al-Din Ansari|date=2007|publisher=Mazda Publishers|location=Costa Mesa, California|isbn=978-1568591957|pages=1\u2013355}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Maeda|first1=Hirotake|title=On the Ethno-Social Background of Four Ghol\u0101m Families from Georgia in Safavid Iran|journal=Studia Iranica|publisher=Peeters Publishers|date=2003|issue=32|doi=10.2143/SI.32.2.563203|pages=1\u2013278}}\n* {{cite journal|author-last=Mousavi|author-first=Mohammad A.|editor-last=Asatrian|editor-first=Garnik S.|title=The Autonomous State in Iran: Mobility and Prosperity in the Reign of Shah 'Abbas the Great (1587\u20131629)|journal=Iran and the Caucasus|date=2008|volume=12|issue=1|doi=10.1163/157338408X326172|pages=17\u201333|jstor=25597352|publisher=Brill}}\n\n{{Safavid Provinces}}\n\n[[Category:Safavid Empire|Georgia]]\n[[Category:16th century in Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:17th century in Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:18th century in Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:Kingdom of Kartli]]\n[[Category:Kingdom of Kakheti]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Safavid Georgia\n|native_name = Vel\u0101yat-e Gorjest\u0101n\n|common_name = Gorjestan\n|government_type  = [[Velayat]]\n|life_span    = 1510s \u2013 1736\n|era          = \n|status       = Province of the [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid Empire]]\n|p1           = \n|flag_p1      = \n|p2           =\n|flag_p2      = \n|s1           = Afsharid dynasty\n|flag_s1      = Nader_Shah_Flag.svg\n|s2           = \n|flag_s2      = \n|image_coat   = \n|image_flag   = \n|image_map    = Northwestern part of the Safavid Empire (cropped, v2).png\n|image_map_caption  = Northwestern part of the Safavid Empire\n|national_motto   = \n|national_anthem  = \n|capital          = [[Tiflis]] (Tbilisi)\n|common_languages = [[Georgian language|Georgian]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]]\n|currency         = \n|title_leader = \n|leader1      = \n|leader2      = \n|title_deputy = \n|deputy1      = \n|deputy2      = \n|stat_area3 = \n|stat_pop1 =\n|today={{flag|Armenia}}<br>{{flag|Azerbaijan}}<br>{{flag|Georgia}}<br>{{flag|Russia}}\n}}\nThe '''province of Georgia''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0648\u0644\u0627\u06cc\u062a \u06af\u0631\u062c\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646|translit=Vel\u0101yat-e Gorjest\u0101n}}) was a ''[[vilayat|velayat]]'' (province) of the [[Safavid Empire]] located in the area of present-day [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=17\u201318}} The territory of the province was principally made up of the two subordinate eastern Georgian kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Kartli|Kartli]] ({{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0627\u0631\u062a\u0644\u06cc|translit=Kartil}}) and [[Kingdom of Kakheti|Kakheti]] ({{lang-fa|\u06a9\u0627\u062e\u062a\u06cc|translit=Kakhet}}) and, briefly, parts of the [[Samtskhe\u2013Saatabago|Principality of Samtskhe]].{{efn|Eastern Samtskhe was part of the Safavid Empire from 1551 to 1582, as well as for several years after 1613.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=85}}}} The city of [[Tbilisi|Tiflis]] (present-day Tbilisi) was its administrative center, the base of Safavid power in the province, and the seat of the rulers of Kartli. It also housed an important Safavid [[Mint (facility)|mint]].\n\nSafavid rule was mainly exercised through the approval or appointment of Georgian royals of the [[Bagrationi dynasty]], at times converts to [[Shia Islam]], as ''[[W\u0101li|valis]]'' or ''[[Khan (title)|khan]]s''.{{efn|Before [[Abbas I of Persia|Abbas I]]'s reign (1588\u20131629), governors of Georgia were usually referred to as ''hakem''.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=83}} Sometimes they were also styled as ''[[sultan|soltan]] (salatin)''.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=86}}}} The eastern Georgian kingdoms had been subjected in the early 16th century, their rulers did not commonly convert. Tiflis was garrisoned by an Iranian force as early as Ismail{{nbsp}}I's reign, but relations between the Georgians and Safavids at the time mostly bore features of traditional [[vassalage]]. [[David XI of Kartli|Davud Khan]] (David XI) was the first Safavid-appointed ruler, whose placement on the throne of Kartli in 1562 marked the start of nearly two and a half centuries of [[Iran]]ian political control of eastern Georgia. During the same period, [[Culture of Iran|Iranian cultural]] influence dominated eastern Georgia.\n\nFrom [[Tahmasp I]]'s reign onwards ({{reign|1524|1576}}), the province was of great strategic importance. Many ethnic [[Georgians]], generally from Kartli and Kakheti, rose to prominence in the Safavid state. These men held many of the highest positions in the civil and military administration, and many women entered the harem of the ruling class. By the late Safavid period, Georgians formed the mainstay of the Safavid army as well. The establishment of a large [[Iranian Georgians|Georgian community in Iran]] proper dates back to the era of Safavid suzerainty in Georgia. As the province was a border entity, the ''valis'' of Georgia exercised more autonomy than other provinces of the Safavid empire; it could therefore be compared to the Arabestan Province (present-day [[Khuzestan Province]]), in the southwestern part of the empire.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=17\u201318}} The province of Georgia was one of only four Safavid administrative territories where governors were consistently given the title of ''vali''.\n\n==History==\n{{History of Georgia (country)}}\n\n===16th century===\nThe first [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid]] king (''[[shah]]'') [[Ismail I]] ({{Reign}}1501\u20131524) made the two kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Kartli|Kartli]] and [[Kingdom of Kakheti|Kakheti]] his [[Vassal state|vassals]] as early as the 1510s.{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|pages=164, 166}} However, distracted by the task of establishing power in [[Iran]], he did not tighten his hold on [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]. He did raid Georgia a number of times, notably in 1518, which reconfirmed its status as a vassal, and in 1522, which resulted in Tiflis being garrisoned by a large Safavid force, but it was only under his son and successor [[Tahmasp I]] (r.{{nbsp}}1524\u20131576) that a genuine province with Safavid-appointed rulers and governors began to take shape.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=166}}\n\nTahmasp I undertook active steps to integrate Georgia into the Safavid domains. His four campaigns against [[Luarsab I of Kartli]] (1540\u20131541, 1546\u20131547, 1551, and 1553\u20131554) resulted in the re-occupation of Kartli, and a Safavid force was permanently stationed in [[Tiflis]] in 1551.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}{{sfn|Floor|2008|pages=295\u2013296}} A key outcome of these campaigns, apart from cementing Safavid hold in central-eastern Georgia, was that they brought to Iran proper (hereafter, simply \"Iran\") large numbers of Georgian prisoners of war.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} Beyond this, the sons of notable Georgians were frequently brought up at the shah's court as part of their tributary relationship with the Safavids.{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=28}} Beginning with the rule of Tahmasp{{nbsp}}I, Georgians would contribute greatly to the character of Safavid society and play a major role in its army and civil administration.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} This newly introduced ethnic element in the Safavid state would later be known in historiography as the \"third force\" alongside the two \"founding elements\" of the Safavid state, the Persians and the Turkomans.{{efn|The \"third force\" included the [[Circassians]] and [[Armenians]].}} \n[[File:Safavid_Courtiers_Leading_Georgian_Captives_(The_Metropolitan_Museum_of_Art).jpg|thumb|150px|right|Safavid courtiers leading Georgian captives. A mid-16th century Persian textile panel from the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].]]\nIn 1551 the Safavids gained the eastern part of the [[Samtskhe\u2013Saatabago|principality of Samtskhe]].{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=173}}{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=85}} In 1555, during Tahmasp{{nbsp}}I's reign, the [[Peace of Amasya]] was signed with the neighboring [[Ottoman Empire]]. According to the terms of the treaty, eastern Georgia (including eastern Samtskhe) remained in Iranian hands while western Georgia (including western Samtskhe) ended up in Turkish hands.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=xxxi}} To speed up the process of integration into the empire, Tahmasp{{nbsp}}I imposed numerous Iranian political and social institutions such as bilingual Georgian\u2013Persian ''[[Firman|farm\u00e2ns]]'', with the aim of establishing Persian as the official administrative language of Safavid Georgia.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} It was also during his reign that the first Georgian royal, a convert to Islam named [[Daud Khan of Kartli|Davud Khan]] (1569\u20131578) was put on the puppet throne in Tiflis.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} These events marked the start of almost 250 years of Iranian political dominance, with a few brief intermissions, over eastern Georgia.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=48}}\n\nIn 1559, the first provincial [[vizier]] was assigned to the [[Azerbaijan (Iran)|Azerbaijan]] province, with authority over the Georgia province as well as [[Safavid Shirvan|Shirvan]] including [[Shaki, Azerbaijan|Shakki]].{{sfn|Floor|2001|pages=108-109}} These provincial viziers, also known as royal viziers, held the title of ''vazir-e koll'', and received instructions from the central government located in the royal capital, instead of the local governor.{{sfn|Floor|2001|pages=108-109}} Challenging the Safavid possession of eastern Caucasus, the Ottomans invaded the Georgian polities [[Lala Mustafa Pasha's Caucasian campaign|in a victorious campaign]] in 1578. As a result, the Safavids released the Georgian rebel ruler [[Simon I of Kartli|Shahnavaz Khan]] (Simon{{nbsp}}I of Kartli) from captivity to enable him to join the fight against the Ottomans.{{efn|Simon I was earlier known for his fierce resistance against the Safavid domination, which resulted in his being imprisoned for several years at the [[Alamut Castle]].}} Though Simon achieved considerable success in Kartli, he was eventually captured by the Ottoman troops and died in captivity in Constantinople.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} In the period 1580\u20131581 the Safavid government sent a force accompanied by the ''[[tupchi-bashi]]'' Morad Khan to Georgia together with a number of cannon founders and the materials needed for casting cannon.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=233}} By 1582 the Ottomans were in control of the eastern, Safavid portion of Samtskhe.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=85}} Unable to resist the Ottoman invasion, [[Manuchar II Jaqeli]] of Samtskhe accepted the Iranian overlordship as well and moved to the Safavid court, where he lived until his death in 1614.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} By the [[Treaty of Constantinople (1590)|Treaty of Constantinople]] in 1590, the Safavids lost control over Georgia as they were forced to recognize the whole province as an Ottoman possession.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}\n\n===17th century===\n\n[[File:\u10e0\u10dd\u10e1\u10e2\u10dd\u10db_\u10ee\u10d0\u10dc\u10d8.gif|thumb|150px|left|[[Rostom of Kartli|Rostam Khan]] (Rostom), ''vali'' of Kartli, eastern Georgia, 1633\u20131658]]\nAt the beginning of the rule of [[Abbas I of Persia|Abbas I]], the importance of Georgia and the influence of ethnic Georgians in the Safavid state increased and they came to be known as the \"third force\". Already by 1595 an ethnic Georgian from Kartli, [[Allahverdi Khan]], originally surnamed [[Undiladze]], had become one of the most powerful figures in the Safavid state.{{sfn|Savory|2007|page=81}} By the end of the 16th{{nbsp}}century, Georgians, forming an increasingly influential military faction, became a major threat to the [[Qizilbash]], the traditional backbone of the Safavid army.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} At the same time, the Georgians at the Safavid court vied for influence among each other as well as against their [[Circassians|Circassian]] counterparts.{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=17}} By and large, Abbas{{nbsp}}I's policy towards the province can be seen as a continuing the previous efforts to fully integrate the area in the Safavid Empire.\n\nIn the early years of the 17th century, Abbas re-established Safavid influence in eastern Georgia. There was a resistance in Kakheti in 1605, when the rebels overthrew pro-Iranian patricide [[Constantine I of Kakheti|Constantine Khan]] and Abbas{{nbsp}}I acceded to their demands to approve [[Teimuraz I of Kakheti|Tahmuras Khan]] (Teimuraz{{nbsp}}I) as the new king of Kakheti.{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=50}}{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} At the same time, he also confirmed [[Luarsab II of Kartli|Lohrasb]] (Luarsab{{nbsp}}II) as ''vali'' of Kartli. However, when Lohrasb started to work against Safavid interests and refused to convert to Islam, Abbas{{nbsp}}I had him incarcerated in [[Astarabad]] and later executed in [[Shiraz]].{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}\n\nIn 1607 Abbas appointed [[Manuchar III Jaqeli]] as ruler of (eastern) Samtskhe.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} By 1613\u20131614 Abbas had restored Safavid control over eastern Samtskhe.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=85}} In 1614\u20131617, as a punishment for disobedience shown by his formerly loyal subjects Lohrasb and Tahmuras Khan, Abbas{{nbsp}}I launched several [[Abbas I's Kakhetian and Kartlian campaigns|major punitive campaigns]] in his Georgian territories. These campaigns resulted in the sack of [[Tiflis]], the ravaging of the entire area, the massacre of many tens of thousands, and the deportation of hundreds of thousands of ethnic Georgians to Iran.{{sfn|Blow|2009|page=174}}{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pages=291, 536}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=191}} These deportees further augmented the [[Iranian Georgians|Georgian community in Iran]].{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=536}} In the meantime, Abbas{{nbsp}}I appointed [[Bagrat VII of Kartli|Bagrat Khan]] as governor of Kartli, and [[Bektash of Kakheti|Bektash Beg Torkman]] as governor of Kakheti.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=164}} In 1619 Abbas{{nbsp}}I appointed Bagrat's son [[Simon II of Kartli|Semayun Khan]], a loyalist born and raised in [[Isfahan]], as khan, or ''vali'', of Kartli, and appointed another non-royal Safavid official as governor of Kakheti, in order to maintain a tight grip on this part of the province.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=600}} He also moved many Qizilbash tribal folk to the Georgia province in order to strengthen central control.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=145}} From the mid-1610s onwards, Kakheti was often under the direct governorship of [[Qizilbash]] lords.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=86}}\n\nAround 1620 Abbas relocated some 8,000 [[History of the Jews in Georgia|Jews]] from the province, along with 40,000 Armenians, to the newly built city of [[Farahabad, Mazandaran|Farahabad]].{{sfn|Matthee|1999|page=44}} In these years, he moved a total of about 15,000 families from the [[Caucasus]] to [[Mazandaran Province|Mazandaran]].{{sfn|Blow|2009|page=105}}{{efn|Amongst the deportees there were also Muslims from Georgia, and sections of the [[Safavid Shirvan|Shirvan]] and [[Safavid Qarabagh|Karabakh]] population.}}\nIn 1624\u201325 Manuchar III Jaqeli, appointed earlier by Abbas{{nbsp}}I as nominal ruler of Samtskhe, moved to Kartli to join the rebellion of [[Giorgi Saakadze|Murav-Beg]] (Giorgi Saakadze) against Safavid rule.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pages=194, 379}} Some time later, while away from Samtskhe, he decided to accept Ottoman suzerainty.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pages=194, 379}} However, when he returned to Samtskhe in 1625 for negotiations in the western (Ottoman) part of Samtskhe, he was killed by his own uncle.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pages=194, 379}} Subsequently, the Ottomans incorporated the western part of Samtskhe as a [[Eyalet|pashalik]].{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=52}} The Safavids retained control of the eastern part.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=140}} The remaining century of Safavid rule in Georgia, after Abbas{{nbsp}}I's death in 1629, was marked by unprecedented Iranian influence.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} Under the ''vali'' [[Rostom of Kartli|Khosrow Mirza]], Safavid Georgia saw a period of relative peace and prosperity. In return for his loyalty, the then-incumbent king, [[Safi of Persia|Safi]] ({{reign|1629|1642}}), had given him the title of Rostam Khan, and had made him governor of Kartli, a post which he held for more than twenty years. Kakheti however, came under direct Safavid rule.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}}\n\nRostam Khan was a childless [[widower]], however, and thus needed a wife and offspring. Being the loyal servant he was, after consulting the Safavid king, Rostam was allowed to marry a sister of [[Levan II Dadiani]], [[Principality of Mingrelia|ruler of Mingrelia]] (western Georgia), named [[Mariam Dadiani|Mariam]].{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} The marriage fit well with the political ambitions of the Safavid state and of Rostam himself.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} Not only would this alliance with the Dadiani, i.e. Mingrelia, give Rostam an ally against Tahmuras Khan (Teimuraz{{nbsp}}I) and [[George III of Imereti]], but it would also provide Rostam with a line of successors who would be as loyal to the Safavid crown as he was.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} Also important was the fact that it would enhance Safavid plans to conquer [[Kingdom of Imereti|Imereti]].{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} It would create a perfect circumstance if a campaign was needed against the Ottomans, with whom they [[Ottoman\u2013Safavid War (1623\u201339)|were at war at the time]] over Imereti.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} King Safi paid for the wedding gifts, and sent some 50,000 ''marchil'', roughly half a ton of silver, to the ruler of Mingrelia, and provided him with an annual salary of 1,000 ''[[Iranian toman|tomans]]'' (3-gram gold coins); an alliance was thus founded with the Mingrelians.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}} The marriage preparations alarmed the Imeretians. The groom's party was a 30,000-strong army marching to meet Levan's heavily armed entourage. George{{nbsp}}III of Imereti blocked the border with Kartli, compelling Rostom's wedding party to take a circuitous route via [[Akhaltsikhe]], and intercepted Dadiani on his way to the marriage, but he was defeated and taken prisoner by Levan at the Kaka Bridge near [[Baghdati]].{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=199}}\n\nIn 1639, by the [[Treaty of Zuhab]] which ended the 1623\u20131639 war, the Caucasus was decisively partitioned between the Safavids and Ottomans roughly along the lines of the earlier Amasya treaty of 1555. Kartli and Kakheti were reconfirmed as Iranian domains, while everything to the west of it remained in Ottoman hands. Samtskhe\u2013Meskheti, including its eastern part, was irrevocably lost.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=85}}\n\nIn 1654, during the reign of King [[Abbas II of Persia|Abbas II]] ({{reign|1642|1666}}), Kartli was turned into crown land (''khasseh''), and therefore subjected to direct Safavid taxation.{{sfn|Barendse|2002|page=209}}{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=309}} The amount of land directly taxed by the state reached its greatest extent in this year.{{sfn|Barendse|2002|page=209}} Also during Abbas{{nbsp}}II's reign, an earlier plan was revived to populate the eastern part of the province, Kakheti, with Turkic nomads. This measure incited [[Bakhtrioni Uprising|a general uprising]] in 1659. The rebels succeeded in expelling the nomads, but still had to accept the Safavid kings's suzerainty.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} In 1675 a wall was built around Tiflis by king [[Suleiman I of Persia|Suleiman I]] (1666\u20131694).{{sfn|Rayfield|2012|page=211}} By the 1690s ethnic [[Georgians]] formed the mainstay of the Safavid army.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=114}}\n\n===18th century===\n\nIn 1701 one of the artillerymen (''tupchis'') in Tiflis was appointed ''vakil'' (\"regent\") of the ''[[tupchi-bashi]]'' of Tiflis fortress.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=198}} [[David II of Kakheti|Emamqoli Khan]] (David{{nbsp}}II), born and raised in [[Isfahan]], and known for his loyal service to his Safavid overlords, was made governor of Kakheti in 1703\u20131709 by [[Sultan Husayn]] ({{reign|1694|1722}}) due to his father, [[Heraclius I of Kakheti|Nazar-Ali Khan]] (Heraclius{{nbsp}}I), being stationed at Isfahan during the entire period.\n\n[[File:1708._\u10d3\u10d0\u10d5\u10d8\u10d7_II-\u10e1_\u10ec\u10e7\u10d0\u10da\u10dd\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1_\u10d2\u10d0\u10dc\u10d0\u10ee\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1_\u10e1\u10d8\u10d2\u10d4\u10da\u10d8.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[David II of Kakheti|Emamqoli Khan]] (David{{nbsp}}II of Kakheti)]]\nIn 1709, following his father's death, he was formally appointed as the new governor of Kakheti. However, until 1715, he served as ''vali in absentia'' due to his being obliged to stay at the court in Isfahan.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=249}} To the west, in Kartli, the administration was given to two successive governors who both served as ''vali in absentia'' due to being stationed in other parts of the empire: [[George XI of Kartli|Shah-Navaz Khan II, Gorgin Khan]] (George XI); and [[Kaikhosro of Kartli|Kaykhosrow Khan]]. Due to this, in the years 1703\u20131714, the administration there was led by two successive regents (''janeshins'') namely [[Levan of Kartli|Shah-Qoli Khan]] (Levan) and [[Vakhtang VI of Kartli|Hosayn-Qoli Khan]] (Vakhtang{{nbsp}}VI).\n\nIn 1712\u20131719 Hosayn-Qoli Khan was forced to stay in Iran, and the Safavid king therefore gave the governorships of Kartli to others, amongst them [[Jesse of Kartli|Ali-Qoli Khan]] (Jesse) and ''janeshins'' such as [[Prince Bakar of Kartli|Shah-Navaz, Bakar Mirza]]. In 1719 the Iranian government decided to send Hosayn-Qoli Khan, who had occupied several other high positions since 1716, back to Georgia with the task of handling the Lezgin rebellion.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=225}} Assisted by the ruler of neighboring Kakheti, as well as the governor (''beglarbeg'') of [[Safavid Shirvan|Shirvan]], Hosayn-Qoli made significant progress in putting a halt to the Lezgins.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=225}} However, in the winter of 1721, at a crucial moment in the campaign, he was recalled.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=225}} The order, which came after the fall of grand vizier [[Fath-Ali Khan Daghestani]], was made at the instigation of the eunuch faction within the royal court, who had persuaded the shah that a successful end to the campaign would do the Safavid realm more harm than good. In their view, it would enable Vakhtang, the Safavid ''[[Vali (governor)|vali]]'', to form an alliance with Russia with an eye to conquering Iran.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=225}} Shortly after, the Lezgins overran [[Safavid Shirvan|Shirvan]], whereafter they [[Sack of Shamakhi (1721)|sacked and looted]] the provincial capital of [[Shamakhi]] and massacred much of its population. In 1722 Emamqoli Khan died and was buried in [[Qom, Iran|Qom]]. Sultan Husayn then appointed his brother [[Constantine II of Kakheti|Mahmad Qoli Khan]] (Constantine{{nbsp}}II) as the new governor of Kakheti.\n\nWhen the capital of Isfahan was put under [[Siege of Isfahan|siege in 1722]], Hosayn-Qoli Khan defied the royal orders and refused to send the requested relief force.{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=54}} In the meantime, Russia took full advantage of the situation. With the Safavids on the brink of collapse, they launched a campaign in 1722\u20131723 that resulted in the [[Russo-Persian War (1722\u20131723)|annexation of the coastal territories]]. The Ottomans, also taking advantage of the situation, overran the province of Georgia and other territories to the west of the area that the Russians had captured.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=142}} By the [[Treaty of Constantinople (1724)|Treaty of Constantinople]], the two powers further divided the annexed territories between them, with the Ottomans again retaining Georgia.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|pages=226\u2013227}} The rebellious Hosayn-Qoli Khan, who had sided with the Russians during their invasion in 1722\u20131723, in what turned out to be an ill-fated alliance, died in exile in Russia in 1737. When the Safavids were restored by [[Nader Shah|Nader Qoli Beg]] (later known as Nader Shah), the ''[[de facto]]'' ruler of Iran, he restored Iranian dominance in the Caucasus and made [[Teimuraz II of Kakheti|Teimuraz II]] ''vali'' of Kakheti, while appointing an Iranian as the governor of Kartli.{{sfn|Hitchins|2001|pages=464\u2013470}} In 1736 Nader deposed the Safavids and became king himself, establishing the [[Afsharid dynasty]].\n\n==Mint==\n[[File:Eight Safavid abbasis struck at the Tiflis mint.jpg|thumb|right|Silver ''abbasis'' minted in Tiflis during the reign of Sultan Husayn ({{Reign|1694|1722}}), with minting dates varying from 1717\u20131718 to 1719\u20131720.]]\n[[File:Safavid shahis struck at the Tiflis mint.jpg|thumb|right|Silver ''panj shahis'' minted in Tiflis in 1716\u20131717 during the reign of Sultan Husayn.]]\n{{see also|Abbasi (currency)|Georgian abazi}}\nOne of the most important Safavid [[Mint (facility)|mint]]s was located in the province of Georgia, in Tiflis. Close to the border with the Ottoman Empire, the Tiflis mint was important to the Safavids, for [[bullion]] (i.e. silver bars, Spanish [[Spanish real|reals]], Dutch [[rijksdaalder]]s) for the minting of coins was largely imported from and through the Ottoman Empire (and Russia).{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=68}}{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=53}} Upon arrival in Iran, the bullion was always brought to Tiflis, Erivan, or Tabriz to be melted into Iranian coins.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=5, 15}} Tiflis was thus a major stopping point for merchants who returned with silver.{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=68}} It was also one of the few mints, alongside the ones at Tabriz and [[Yerevan|Erivan]] (Yerevan), where re-minting took place.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=53}} In the 17th century the Tiflis mint was one of the most active Safavid mints.{{sfn|Barendse|2002|page=221}}\n\nThe Tiflis mint also lay on a route widely used by silk traders.{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=68}} According to French traveller [[Jean Baptiste Tavernier]], traders who went to Gilan to negotiate over silk, went to the mint at Tiflis, for the mint master (''zarrab-bashi'') gave a 2%{{nbsp}}discount on silver for silk traders.{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|page=68}} Tavernier notes that this is partly due to the silver coins from Tiflis being a little less [[Fineness|fine]].{{sfn|Babaie|Babayan|Baghdiantz-McCabe|Farhad|2004|pages=68\u201369}}\n\nThe coins minted at Tiflis were mostly used for the local citizens, rather than for the local Safavid garrison.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=17}} The coins always had to bear the Safavid rulers' name and follow the Safavid types, legends, and weight standards.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=17\u201318}} In many other regards, however, the appointed ''valis'' were granted a great deal of autonomy in terms of minting practises.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=17\u201318}} For example, the ''vali'' reportedly was allowed to benefit from the profit accrued by the mints in the province.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=17}}\n\nDuring the reign of Suleiman I, the economic situation worsened.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=130\u2013131}} The amount of precious metal coming into the country decreased, and as a result the quality of the coins diminished.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|pages=130\u2013131}} This deficiency in weight was also apparent in coins from the Tiflis mint; in 1688, the ''abbasis'' and ''mahmudis'' struck at the mint were 22.5% below the standard weight they were supposed to have.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=131}} The royal treasury was aware of the issue, and subsequently stopped accepting ''mahmudis'' that had been minted in Tiflis.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=131}}\n\nIn the years 1682\u20131685 the only Safavid mints that were recorded as active were the ones at Tiflis and [[Tabriz]].{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=119}} According to a 1687 report, money played close to no role in Georgia.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=44}} French botanist [[Joseph Pitton de Tournefort]] confirms this: according to his texts of 1701, people in large parts of Georgia preferred to be paid in materials such as bracelets, rings, necklaces, and so forth.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=44}}\n\n==Stationed military force==\nThe province of Georgia hosted many Safavid soldiers, as it was considered a territory of the utmost importance. At the same time, it was a province that bordered the Ottoman Empire.{{sfn|Floor|2001|pages=82\u201383}} A Safavid force was permanently stationed in Tiflis from 1551 onwards.{{sfn|Floor|2008|pages=295\u2013296}} According to [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] reports, some 4,000 Safavid cavalry were stationed in Georgia and [[Ganja, Azerbaijan|Ganja]] in the 1570s.{{sfn|Floor|2001|pages=135\u2013136}} According to traveller [[Jean Chardin]], towards the end of Abbas{{nbsp}}I's reign many troops were stationed in Georgia, of which some 5,000 were \"battle-experienced and trained\".{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=207}} In the mid-17th century, during the reign of [[Abbas II of Persia|Abbas II]] (1642\u20131666), some 50,000 Safavid troops were stationed in the province according to Chardin's figures.{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=145}} The French missionary and traveller P\u00e8re Sanson, who was in the Safavid Empire during the latter part of King [[Suleiman I of Persia|Suleiman I]]'s reign (1666\u20131694), wrote that a \"large number\" of troops were stationed in Georgia.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=212}} Towards the end of Sultan Husayn's reign (1694\u20131722), the troops at the behest of the then-governor of Kartli, [[Vakhtang VI of Kartli|Hosayn-Qoli Khan]] (Vakhtang{{nbsp}}VI), numbered some 10,000 [[Georgians]] and 3,000\u20134,000 [[Iranian peoples|Iranians]].{{sfn|Matthee|2012|page=225}}\n\nThe ''vali'' of Georgia had a corps of ''[[Qurchi (royal bodyguard)|qurchis]]'' at his disposal, including a ''[[qurchi-bashi]]'', and a legion of specialized qurchis for his \"[[accoutrements]]\" (i.e. ''qurchi-e zereh'', ''qurchi-e kafsh'', ''qurchi-e tarkesh'', etc.).{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=149}} They also had the institution of ''vakil'' (\"regent\"), who could take care of all matters in case it was needed.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=7}}{{efn|The ''vakil'' sometimes also functioned as a tutor (''[[Lala (title)|laleh]]''), in cases when the governor was young.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=7}}}}\n\n==Silk and wine production==\nAlthough the province contributed to the overall [[silk]] production, its silk was said, together with that of [[Karabakh Beylarbeylik|Karabakh\u2013Ganja]], to be of lesser quality than that of [[Gilan Province|Gilan]] and [[Mazandaran Province|Mazandaran]].{{sfn|Matthee|1999|page=37}} Following [[Abbas I of Persia|Abbas I]]'s (1588\u20131629) decisive subduing of Georgia, he ordered that the province should produce more silk in the future.{{sfn|Matthee|1999|page=41}} According to Nicolaas Jacobus Overschie, a [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] representative in the Safavid Empire, of the 2,800 bales of silk that had been produced in 1636, the provinces of Georgia and Karabakh\u2013Ganja had yielded a total of 300 bales.{{sfn|Matthee|1999|page=41}}\n\nAccording to Jean Chardin, the wines produced in Georgia and Shiraz were of excellent quality.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=44}} Every six months the province of Georgia supplied the royal [[wine cellars]] of the Safavid court with some three hundred liters of wine, as part of the total amount of taxes it paid.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|pages=43\u201344}} The governors were responsible for the supervision of the [[viticulture]] of their province.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=44}}\n\n==Cultural influences==\n===Georgian culture===\nFrom the 16th century there was an increase of Iranian influence in Georgian culture.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}} The genres in which it was most apparent were [[Georgian literature|literature]], painting, and [[Georgian architecture|architecture]].{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}} During the Safavid period, many Georgian rulers, princes, and nobles had spent time in Iran. Therefore, Iranian traditions also spread throughout Georgia.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}} The placement of [[David XI of Kartli|Davud Khan]] (David XI) on the puppet throne of Kartli in 1562 did not just initiate a lengthy period of Iranian political dominance; in the same two and a half centuries that followed, until the [[Georgia within the Russian Empire|coming]] of the [[Russian Empire|Russians]] in the 19th century, [[Culture of Iran|Iranian cultural]] influence dominated eastern Georgia (Kartli\u2013Kakheti).{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=48}} According to Jean Chardin, who was in Georgia in 1672, the Georgians followed Iranian traditions.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}} Chardin assumed that the process had been influenced by those nobles who had converted to Islam (in order to obtain positions as state officials), as well as those who encouraged their female relatives to become ladies at court.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}}\n\nIn the Safavid period, \"a great number of books\" were translated from Persian into Georgian. The ''Rostomiani'', the Georgian version of the ''[[Shahnameh]]'', was further developed and improved, as well as ''[[Visramiani]]'', the Georgian version of ''[[Vis o Ramin]]''.{{sfn|Gelashvili|2012|page=494}} According to a letter sent to the Pope by a Catholic missionary who [[Floruit|flourished]] in the 17th century, Padre Bernardi, it was to his \"great regret\" that literate Georgians preferred to read works such as the ''Rostomiani'' (''[[Shahnameh]]''), ''Bezhaniani'', and ''Baramguriani'' and were less interested in religious texts.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}}\n\n[[Teimuraz I of Kakheti]] (Tahmuras Khan) is perhaps mostly remembered for creating issues for the central government, but he was fluent in Persian and fond of Persian poetry, which he \"highly valued\".{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} In his words:{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}}\n\n{{quote|The sweetness of Persian speech urged me to compose the music of verse.}}\n\nTeimuraz wrote several poems influenced by the contemporary Persian tradition, packed with \"Persian imagery and allusions, loanwords, and phraseology\". A later Georgian ruler, Vakhtang{{nbsp}}VI (Hosayn-Qoli Khan), was also important in this regard.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} When he was forced to stay in Iran, he learned to excel in Persian. He later used this skill to translate works into Georgian.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} He created a Georgian version of the Persian ''[[Qabus-Nama|Qabusnameh]]'' known as ''Amirnasariani'' (\"The story of Amirnasar\", Amirnasar being the mythical Iranian king [[Kaykavus]]). During his detention in Iran, Vakhtang also translated into Georgian Kashefi's ''[[Panchatantra|Kal\u012bleh o Demneh]]''.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} Later, back in Georgia, he ordered the entire story to be translated once more, while his tutor, [[Sulkhan-Saba Orbeliani]], also made a revised version of Vakhtang's own translation.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} Though Vakhtang, individually, was heavily involved in further developing Georgian-Iranian literary ties (in other words, by his own writings), he also founded an entire school dedicated to translators from Persian into Georgian.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} During this period, a number of folk stories (i.e. ''[[dastan]]s'') that were extremely popular in Iran, were translated into Georgian on his orders.{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}} One of these was the ''Bakhtiarnameh'', a collection of several novellas, as well as the ''Baramgulandamiani'' (\"Bahram o Golandam\"), originally written by Katebi Nishapuri. The many other Persian-Georgian literary efforts of this era include translations of the [[Quran|Qur'an]] and books on Shia [[jurisprudence]].{{sfn|Gvakharia|2001|pages=481\u2013486}}{{sfn|Giunashvili|2016}}\n\n===Iranian culture===\nIn another, perhaps unorthodox, way Georgia also influenced the culture of Iran. According to a story, an ethnic Georgian named Scedan Cilaze was so renowned for being able to \"hold\" his liquor, that Safavid King [[Safi of Persia|Safi]] ({{reign|1629|1642}}) invited him to the court in order to hold a drinking competition.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}} After beating everyone at court, the king himself challenged Cilaze, and reportedly died doing so. Though Prof. Matthee reports that the story may be \"apocryphal\", as alcoholism did kill Safi, but not in relation to a drinking contest, it does show that Georgian habits had spread to Iran.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}}\n\nIn the Safavid period, large numbers of ethnic Georgian men entered Safavid government service, whereas many Georgian women entered the harems of the ruling elite and the royal court.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}} Drinking alcohol, a prominent Georgian habits, influenced Iranian society, and more importantly, court culture, during this period.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}} It is especially evident in the taxes the province had to pay{{snd}}they included many liters of wine. The royal harem, the private area of the royal court, was where Safavid rulers grew up; after Abbas{{nbsp}}I's reign, all Safavid rulers grew up there surrounded by mostly Georgian women.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}} There were also many ''[[Military of the Safavid dynasty#Gholam|gholams]]'' who drank. Matthee therefore suggests that it is quite likely that the \"fondness\" for wine exhibited by Safavid rulers originated in this environment.{{sfn|Matthee|2005|page=43}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of rulers of Safavid Georgia]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last1=Babaie|first1=Sussan|last2=Babayan|first2=Kathryn|last3=Baghdiantz-McCabe|first3=Ina|last4=Farhad|first4=Massumeh|title=Slaves of the Shah: New Elites of Safavid Iran|date=2004|publisher=I.B.Tauris|pages=1\u2013256|isbn=978-0857716866|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Barendse|first1=R.J.|title=The Arabian Seas: The Indian Ocean World of the Seventeenth Century|date=2002|location=Armonk, N.Y.|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0765633644|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Blow | first = David | title = Shah Abbas: The Ruthless King Who became an Iranian Legend | year = 2009 | isbn = 978-1845119898 | publisher = I.B.Tauris | location = London, UK | lccn = 2009464064 | url = https://books.google.dk/books?id=K_kBAwAAQBAJ&pg= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Floor|first1=Willem|authorlink=Willem Floor|title=Safavid Government Institutions|date=2001|publisher=Mazda Publishers|location=Costa Mesa, California|isbn=978-1568591353|ref=harv}