{"title_page": "2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine", "text_new": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Quarantine in Luzon}}\n{{update|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current quarantine|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n|title=2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine\n|causes=[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]]\n|date={{start date|2020|03|17|mf=y}}\u2013{{abbr|present|assuming that it does not get lifted early or extended, April 2020 is the expiry date}} (scheduled to expire on {{end date|2020|04|12|mf=y}})\n|image=\n|caption=\n|place=[[Luzon]], [[Philippines]] including its associated islands\n|side3=\n|side2=\n|side1=\n|result=About 57 million people quarantined (all of Luzon)<ref name=\"aljazeera\"/>\n|methods=Checkpoints for checking the motivation for travels, banning of public events, closure of commercial and retail businesses, closure of schools and universities until April 12 and other prohibitions.\n|goals=To contain the outbreak of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in the Philippines\n}}\n\nOn March 16, 2020, [[Rodrigo Duterte]] declared the entire [[Luzon]] area in the Philippines under \"enhanced community [[quarantine]],\" which is effectively a total [[lockdown]], restricting the movement of the population with exceptions, in response to the growing [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|pandemic]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in the country. Additional lockdown restrictions mandated the temporary closure of non-essential shops and businesses. This quarantine came two days after the implementation of the community quarantine of [[Metro Manila]]. The quarantine is expected to last until April 2020.\n\n== Background ==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\nFollowing the outbreak of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) which started in [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China, the Philippine government confirmed the country's first case of the disease on January 30, 2020, when the virus was detected in a Chinese national who traveled from Wuhan, China and Hong Kong.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/30/20/philippines-confirms-first-case-of-new-coronavirus|title=Philippines confirms first case of new coronavirus|date=January 30, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> The second case was confirmed on February 2, with the patient being the husband of the first case who was also Chinese.<ref name=\":01\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/first-coronavirus-death-outside-china-reported-philippines-n1128371|title=First coronavirus death outside China reported in Philippines|date=February 2, 2020|publisher=NBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> Three days later, on February 5, another Chinese national was confirmed to the be third case in the Philippines.<ref name=\"doh3rd\">{{cite web|url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/doh-press-release/doh-confirms-3rd-2019-nCoV-ARD-case-in-PH|title=DOH confirms 3rd 2019-nCoV ARD Case iN PH|date=February 5, 2020|website=Department of Health (Philippines)|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205081612/https://www.doh.gov.ph/doh-press-release/doh-confirms-3rd-2019-nCoV-ARD-case-in-PH|archive-date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> After a month, on March 5, the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] announced that the first Filipino in the Philippines confirmed to be infected with COVID-19 who is also the fourth case while the fifth case is the first case of local transmission since the infected person did not travel outside the Philippines.<ref name=\"DOHNC2\">{{cite news|last1=Punzalan|first1=Jamaine|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/06/20/new-coronavirus-case-in-philippines-possible-local-transmission|title=Philippines' new coronavirus cases now at 5, including potential local transmission|date=March 6, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>[https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1238159/doh-deloitte-ph-employee-is-4th-coronavirus-case-5th-case-is-from-cainta DOH : Deloitte PH employee is 4th coronavirus case; 5th case is from Cainta | Inquirer News]</ref> The sixth case that was confirmed on March 7 is the wife of the fifth case.<ref name=\"codered\">{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/07/20/code-red-philippines-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-6-doh-confirms-local-transmission|title=CODE RED: Philippines' coronavirus cases rise to 6, DOH confirms local transmission|date=March 7, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> In the following days, the number of cases steadily increased.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/253882-new-philippines-novel-coronavirus-cases-march-9-2020|title=Novel coronavirus cases in Philippines spike to 20}}</ref>\n\n== Lockdowns ==\n=== Initial lockdowns ===\n[[File:PNP PRO 3 Checkpoints COVID 19 2.jpg|thumb|Police checkpoint near the border of [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila]] with [[Meycauayan]], [[Bulacan]].]]\nOn March 8, 2020, President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] signed Proclamation 922 placing the entire Philippines under state of public health emergency because of the COVID-19 threat that is looming in the nation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/downloads/2020/02feb/20200308-PROC-922-RRD-1.pdf|title=Proclamation No. 922|date=March 8, 2020|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On the next day, March 9, [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Congressman]] Joey Salceda of the [[Legislative districts of Albay#2nd District|2nd district of the province of Albay]] recommended a [[lockdown]] of the entire [[National Capital Region]] (NCR) for a period of seven days, in response to the COVID-19 threat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728901/lawmaker-wants-weeklong-ncr-lockdown-to-prevent-spread-of-covid-19/story/|title=Lawmaker wants weeklong NCR lockdown amid COVID-19 threat|date=March 9, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Some of his proposals for implementing the lockdown include banning mass transportation and stopping the operation of the [[Philippine expressway network]] that ply to and from the region, and cancelling of classes and work.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Panti|first1=Llanesca|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728901/lawmaker-wants-weeklong-ncr-lockdown-to-prevent-spread-of-covid-19/story/|title=Lawmaker wants weeklong NCR lockdown amid COVID-19 threat|date=March 9, 2020|work=GMA News Online|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> At first, President Rodrigo Duterte turned down the idea because it would \"hamper the flow of basic commodities,\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lopez|first1=Virgil|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729000/duterte-thumbs-down-lockdown-for-metro-manila-over-covid-19/story/?just_in|title=Duterte thumbs down lockdown for Metro Manila over COVID-19|date=March 9, 2020|work=GMA News Online|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> although, Health Secretary [[Francisco Duque]] III, opined that the lockdown may put into effect in some areas where there are reported community-based transmissions, but not the whole NCR.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.ph/news/2020/3/10/Philippines-lockdown-coronavirus.html|title=DOH: 'Localized lockdown' possible amid coronavirus pandemic|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 10, 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nPresident Duterte announced on March 12, 2020 the \"community quarantine\" on [[Metro Manila]] starting at 12 midnight on March 15 up to April 14 that will cover 16 cities and one municipality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/254101-metro-manila-placed-on-lockdown-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Metro Manila to be placed on lockdown due to coronavirus outbreak|last=Talabong|first=Rambo|date=March 12, 2020|website=Rappler|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Traveling through land, domestic air, and domestic sea from Metro Manila was suspended with exceptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/254361-questions-filipinos-metro-manila-coronavirus-lockdown|title=Questions Filipinos are asking about the coronavirus lockdown|last=Baizas|first=Gaby|date=March 13, 2020|website=Rappler|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> For international travel, restrictions are imposed on those who came from countries with localized COVID-19 transmissions, except for citizens of the Philippines (including their foreign spouse and children) or holders of permanent resident visas and diplomat visas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/12/duterte-expands-ban-on-travelers-from-countries-with-local-covid-19-transmissions|title=Duterte expands ban on travelers from countries with local COVID-19 transmissions|last=Geducos|first=Argyll|date=March 13, 2020|website=Manila Bulletin News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Mass transportation vehicles are allowed to operate provided that persons riding these vehicles comply with the social distancing guidelines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/pnp-metro-manila-lockdown.html|title=PNP to man checkpoints in Metro Manila 'lockdown'|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Curfew]] has also put into place by the local government units of Metro Manila.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/15/Coronavirus-COVID-19-updates.html|title=LIVE UPDATES: Metro Manila community quarantine takes effect amid COVID-19 outbreak|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Expansion to Luzon ===\n[[File:COVID-19 Community Quarantine Checkpoint in Cagayan.jpg|thumb|A police-manned checkpoint in [[Tuguegarao]].]]\n[[File:Philippine Red Cross thermal scanning COVID19 Bayombong.jpg|thumb|[[Philippine Red Cross]] volunteers scanning the temperature of commuters entering the provincial capitol in [[Bayombong]], [[Nueva Vizcaya]].]]\nDuring the second day of the implementation of the Metro Manila community quarantine, on March 16, President Duterte declared a Luzon-wide \"enhanced community quarantine\" that aims to further combat the effect of the continuing and increasing spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/iq/254783-full-text-guidelines-luzon-enhanced-community-quarantine|title=GUIDELINES: Luzon 'enhanced community quarantine'|date=March 16, 2020|website=Rappler.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729875/duterte-orders-lockdown-of-entire-luzon-due-to-covid-19-threat/story/|title=COVID-19 THREAT: Duterte orders Luzon-wide 'enhanced community quarantine'|date=March 16, 2020|website=[[GMA News Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> It took effect on March 17 and will end on April 12.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/16/entire-luzon-under-quarantine|title=Entire Luzon under quarantine|last=Geducos|first=Argyll Cyrus|date=March 16, 2020|website=[[Manila Bulletin]] News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1096849|title=Mass transport suspended under enhanced community quarantine|last=Parrocha|first=Azer|last2=Dela Cruz|first2=Raymond Carl|date=March 17, 2020|website=pna.gov.ph|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> This quarantine also applies to the [[Mimaropa|region of Mimaropa]] ([[Mindoro]], [[Marinduque]], [[Romblon]] and [[Palawan]]), which is outside the Luzon island.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://politics.com.ph/coronavirus-lockdown-covers-mimaropa-says-nograles/|title=Coronavirus lockdown covers MIMAROPA, says Nograles|date=March 17, 2020|work=Politko|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Under this new setup, mass gatherings are completely prohibited and all means of public transport is no longer allowed limiting the movement of people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730095/enhanced-community-quarantine-means-lockdown-in-luzon-says-ano/story/|title=Enhanced community quarantine means lockdown in Luzon, says A\u00f1o|last=Bajo|first=Anna Felicia|date=March 17, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Restrictions on the people's movement ====\nAll schools in all levels are temporarily prohibited to conduct classes and activities until April 14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/downloads/2020/03mar/20200316-MEMORANDUM-FROM-ES-RRD.pdf|title=COMMUNITY QUARANTINE OVER THE ENTIRE LUZON AND GUIDELINES FOR THE MANAGEMENT OF THE CORONAVIRUS DISEASE 2019 (COVID-19) SITUATION|last=Medialdea|first=Salvador C.|authorlink=Salvador Medialdea|date=March 16, 2020|website=[[Official Gazette (Philippines)|Official Gazette of the government of the Republic of the Philippines]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=March 20, 2020|access-date=}}</ref> A \"[[Telecommuting|work from home]]\" scheme is applied to the government workers of the [[Executive departments of the Philippines|executive branch]] except for the skeletal workforce consisting of uniformed personnel ([[Philippine National Police]], [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]], and [[Philippine Coast Guard]]), those providing services in the frontline of health and emergency, and border control.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243433/csc-on-work-from-home-arrangement|title=CSC: Work from home scheme for gov\u2019t workers until Luzon quarantine is lifted|last=Ramos|first=Christia Marie|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> For the private sector, companies are also advised to implement a \"work from home\" arrangement.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/luzon-quarantine-a-breakdown-of-the-implementing-guidelines|title=Luzon quarantine: A breakdown of the implementing guidelines|last=Merez|first=Arianne|date=March 17, 2020|website=[[ABS-CBN News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe populace's movement is restricted to their homes and they can only go outside to just buy basic needs such as food, medicines and other things needed for sustenance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/coronavirus-massive-cracks-in-manila-lockdown-luzon-under-enhanced-community-quarantine|title=Coronavirus: Duterte places a third of the Philippines on sweeping lockdown|last=Dancel|first=Raul|date=March 16, 2020|website=[[The Straits Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Only a single person per household can go outside to buy basic necessities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/only-one-person-per-family-allowed-to-leave-house-manila-city-government|title=Only one person per family allowed to leave house \u2013 Manila city government|last=Tiangco|first=Minka|date=March 18, 2020|website=Manila Bulletin News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> In particular, the [[Manila|City of Manila]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/photo/315512/home-quarantine-pass-allows-one-per-household-in-manila-to-go-out-for-supplies/photo/|title=Home quarantine pass allows one per household in Manila to go out for supplies|last=Panganiban-Perez|first=Tina|date=March 19, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> [[Bacoor]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/19/20/bacoor-lockdown-checkpoints-sa-boundaries-quarantine-pass-sa-kada-pamilya|title=Bacoor lockdown: Checkpoints sa boundaries, quarantine pass sa kada pamilya|date=March 19, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|language=tl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> and other places<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1244557/in-bicol-villages-pieces-of-paper-called-quarantine-passes-required-for-residents-leaving-homes|title=In Bicol villages, pieces of paper called \u2018quarantine passes\u2019 required for residents leaving homes|last=Mier-Manjares|first=Ma April|date=March 18, 2020|website=Philippine Daily Inquirer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> issued quarantine passes to persons who were designated by their household would go out their homes to buy needed goods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036629|title=Agoo town to impose \u2018quarantine pass\u2019 to thwart COVID-19 spread|last=Dilim|first=Joanne Namnama P.|date=March 19, 2020|website=pia.gov.ph|publisher=[[Philippine Information Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The \"enhanced community quarantine\" also directs stricter [[social distancing]] protocols where people going to public places must observe one meter distance apart from each other. In connection to this, businesses who provide food and medicine are allowed to operate.<ref name=\"aljazeera\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-philippines-quarantines-island-57-million-people-200316161225532.html|title=Coronavirus: Philippines quarantines island of 57 million people|last=Santos|first=Ana P.|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=Al Jazeera|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Closure of establishments ====\nFurthermore, financial institutions such as bank and money transfer services and utility providers are also not barred to open. Capital markets such as the [[Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas]], the [[Securities and Exchange Commission (Philippines)|Securities and Exchange Commission]], and the [[Philippine Stock Exchange]], were permitted to open only on March 18, provided that skeletal workforce are set up.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/18/2001644/stock-trading-resumes-tomorrow|title=Stock trading resumes tomorrow|last=Gonzales|first=Iris|date=March 18, 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Those industries who act as [[Business process outsourcing in the Philippines|Business Process Outsourcing]] or [[Call center industry in the Philippines|call centers]] as well as export-oriented industries are also allowed to continue with their operations as long as they observe social distancing protocols, temporary shelter for their employees by March 18, and keep up with a skeletal workforce.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Barcelo|first=Vito|url=https://manilastandard.net/news/top-stories/319845/duterte-puts-entire-luzon-on-lockdown.html|title=Duterte puts entire Luzon on lockdown|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[Manila Standard]]|access-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live|last2=Zurbano|first2=Joel|last3=Ramos-Araneta|first3=Macon}}</ref> Hotels and other businesses that provide accommodation are not operational and they are only allowed to lodge foreign guests who have bookings or guests who have long-term leases as of March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/254943-hotel-bookings-banned-coronavirus-lockdown|title=No new hotel bookings during coronavirus lockdown|last=Gotinga|first=J. C.|date=March 18, 2020|website=Rappler|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Travel restrictions ====\n[[File:SM North EDSA Terminal COVID-19 quarantine.jpg|thumb|The usually-filled public transport terminal at the SM North EDSA devoid of any vehicle due to the quarantine measures.]]\nTraveling through air, sea and land is restricted only to diplomats, uniformed workers (especially those who travel with medical supplies, specimens from the laboratory in relation to COVID-19), and those who do humanitarian work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/16/second-headline/look-memorandum-on-enhanced-quarantine/703697/|title=LOOK: Memorandum on enhanced quarantine|date=March 16, 2020|website=[[The Manila Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> People who are going outside the Philippines through Luzon are only limited to [[Overseas Filipino Worker]]s and foreigners;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/19/20/ph-eyes-suspension-of-visa-issuance-amid-covid-19-lockdown|title=PH eyes suspension of visa issuance amid COVID-19 lockdown|date=March 19, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> and they must be escorted by only one person.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/govt-amends-travel-restrictions-travelers-may-leave-through-any-luzon-port-with-conditions|title=Gov't amends travel restrictions; travelers may leave through any Luzon port with conditions|last=Kabiling|first=Genalyn|date=March 18, 2020|website=Manila Bulletin News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the other hand, only [[Philippine nationality law|Filipino citizens]] and diplomats with visas issued by the government of the Philippines are the ones who have permission to enter the Philippines through international airports in Luzon provided that they undergo quarantine procedures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/255000-government-maintains-all-filipinos-abroad-can-return-philippines-despite-luzon-lockdown|title=Filipinos abroad can return to PH despite Luzon lockdown|last=Tomacruz|first=Sofia|date=March 18, 2020|website=Rappler|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> International travelers in transit are also allowed to enter but subject to quarantine procedures too.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/17/c_138887115.htm|title=Philippines to shut down all airports in Luzon starting Friday to curb COVID-19 spread \u2013 Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|date=n.d.|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Foreigners who wish to come to the Philippines can go through Cebu but they must go undergo quarantine procedures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245312/ph-barring-foreigners-dfa-says-no-exceptions?utm_source=izooto&utm_medium=push_notifications&utm_campaign=PHbarringforeignersDFAsaysnoexceptions&utm_content=&utm_term=|title=PH barring foreigners; DFA says no exceptions|last=Pazzibugan|first=Dona Z.|date=March 16, 2020|website=Philippine Daily Inquirer|publisher=Cebu Daily News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> However, this was changed when [[Department of Foreign Affairs (Philippines)|Department of Foreign Affairs]] (DFA) Secretary [[Teodoro Locsin Jr.|Teodoro Locsin Jr]]. announced on March 19 the suspension of visas and visa-free privileges of foreigners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/19/Philippines-DFA-considering-visa-issuance-suspension-Locsin-coronavirus-COVID.html|title=Philippines suspends visa issuance as worldwide COVID-19 cases soar \u2013 Locsin|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Although, DFA clarified on March 20 that there are exceptions.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/20/DFA-visa-issuance-suspension-wont-affect-foreigners-in-PH.html|title=Foreigners already in PH won't be forced to leave despite visa suspension policy, DFA clarifies|date=March 20, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Foreigners who are in the Philippines already or whose visas issued by other government agencies can stay until they depart from the Philippines.<ref name=\":2\" /> In addition, visas is still valid for foreigners who have Filipino spouses or foreigners who have Filipino parents.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nCargo forwarders, farmers, and other food producers are not covered by the travel prohibition but they must go through quarantine checkpoints.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.panaynews.net/farmers-exempted-from-travel-restrictions-during-quarantine-period/|title=Farmers exempted from travel restrictions during quarantine period|date=March 18, 2020|website=Panay News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Those who are guarding or securing an establishment are only permitted to work and travel within the area of their responsibility.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/world/1880700/confusion-as-locked-down-philippines-starts-virus-quarantine|title=Confusion as locked-down Philippines starts virus quarantine|last=Limited|first=Bangkok Post Public Company|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Media practitioners with their vehicles are allowed to go to the quarantine area as long as they get a media pass from the [[Presidential Communications Group (Philippines)|Presidential Communications Operations Office]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1244893/media-personnel-still-allowed-to-travel-cover-during-enhanced-community-quarantine|title=No quarantine period coverage restrictions for duly accredited media personnel|last=Aguilar|first=Krissy|date=March 19, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Terminology ===\n{{See also|Lockdown|Quarantine}}At one point during President Duterte's pronouncement about the Metro Manila \"community quarantine,\" he said that \"they are afraid to call it a lockdown, but it is a lockdown.\"<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Coronavirus/Duterte-orders-Manila-lockdown-from-Sunday|title=Duterte orders Manila lockdown from Sunday|last=Venzon|first=Cliff|date=March 13, 2020|website=[[Nikkei Asian Review]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Petty|first=Martin|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-philippines-casual-idUSKBN20Z2BV|title=Philippine capital on lockdown to contain coronavirus|date=March 12, 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live|last2=Lema|first2=Karen|language=en}}</ref> This statement left many confused.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1096510|title=No lockdown, just 'community quarantine': Nograles|last=Cudis|first=Christine|date=March 13, 2020|website=www.pna.gov.ph|publisher=[[Philippine News Agency]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> His [[Cabinet Secretariat of the Philippines|cabinet secretary]], [[Karlo Nograles]], later made it clear that the proper term is \"community quarantine\" and the President's comment means that the event \"is like a lockdown.\"<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":16\" /> Nograles further said that the term \"lockdown\" can be understood by different interpretations while \"community quarantine\" is a technical term that medical authorities can give meaning and it does not create public fear.<ref name=\":16\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/13/2000574/is-it-lockdown-or-community-quarantine-your-questions-about-latest-move-vs-covid-19-answered|title='Is it a lockdown or a community quarantine?' Your questions about latest move vs COVID-19 answered|last=Cabico|first=Gaea Katreena|date=March 13, 2020|website=philstar.com|publisher=The Philippine Star|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \n\nWhen the \"community quarantine\" was applied to Luzon, [[Presidential Communications Group (Philippines)#Presidential Spokesperson|Presidential Spokeperson]] [[Salvador Panelo]], said that the Luzon-wide \"enhanced community quarantine\" is equivalent to an \"absolute lockdown or total lockdown.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/16/20/duterte-places-luzon-under-enhanced-community-quarantine-to-fight-covid-19|title=Luzon under enhanced community quarantine as COVID-19 cases rise|last=Merez|first=Arianne|date=March 16, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Secretary [[Eduardo A\u00f1o]] of the [[Department of the Interior and Local Government|Department of Interior and Local Government]] also said that \"enhanced community quarantine\" should be considered as a \"total lockdown.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730095/enhanced-community-quarantine-means-lockdown-in-luzon-says-ano/story/|title=Enhanced community quarantine means lockdown in Luzon, says A\u00f1o|last=Bajo|first=Anna Felicia|date=March 17, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Impact and reactions ==\n\n=== Economic ===\nCongressman Joey Salceda who is the House of the Representatives Committee Chairman on Ways and Means said that the Philippines could go into [[recession]] if there is no implementation of a community quarantine, although, he admitted that the  COVID-19 pandemic will affect the [[economy of the Philippines]] in a negative way.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/economy/730787/philippines-could-sink-into-recession-without-community-quarantine/story/|title=Philippines could sink into recession without community quarantine, says Salceda|last=Colcol|first=Erwin|date=March 22, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> According to Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas (BSP) Governor [[Benjamin Diokno]] on March 18, 2020, the economic impact is still not known but \"it will definitely have an impact.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1096999|title=Luzon-wide quarantine to benefit people, economy|last=Villanueva|first=Joann|date=March 18, 2020|website=pna.gov.ph|agency=[[Philippine News Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Two days later, on March 20, 2020, the BSP said that the shutdown of Luzon will slow down the economy of the Philippines with a disruptive impact.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/business/2020/3/20/coronavirus-PH-economy.html|title=COVID-19 to weigh down economic growth for the rest of 2020|last=|first=|date=March 20, 2020|website=CNN Philippines|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> BSP further said the economic impact would last until the second half of 2020 but it is expected to rebound on 2021.<ref name=\":12\" /> \n\nIn other forecast, the domestic output estimates by economic managers for the year 2020 are from 0.3 to 1.0 percentage point.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[National Economic and Development Authority]] revised its 2020 economic growth forecast to 5.5 to 6.5 percent against the targeted 6.5 to 7.5 percent growth, assuming that the COVID-19 problem lasts until June 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/business/2020/3/9/NEDA-growth-forecast-coronavirus.html|title=NEDA lowers PH growth forecast amid coronavirus outbreak|last=|first=|date=March 9, 2020|website=CNN Philippines|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> It is expected that the prices of basic goods will go up to 2.2 percent only compared to 2.5 percent average in 2019.<ref name=\":12\" />  [[Nomura Holdings|Nomura]], a [[Japan|Japanese]] financial [[holding company]], lowered its [[gross domestic product]] (GDP) estimates to the Philippines from 5.6% to 1.6%.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/30/2004400/covid-19-luzon-lockdown-seen-pull-gdp-growth-down-lowest-level-2009|title=COVID-19, Luzon lockdown seen to pull GDP growth down to lowest level since 2009|last=Cigaral|first=Ian Nicolas|date=March 30, 2020|website=philstar.com|publisher=The Philippine Star|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The analysts from the holding company further said that the estimates assume a scenario where the Luzon lockdown ends on the middle of April as scheduled.<ref name=\":13\" /> After the two-day closure of the Philippine Stock Exchange due the Luzon lockdown, the market crashed to about 24 percent reaching the 4,000 level, which is an eight-year low.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nOn March 6, 2020, the [[Asian Development Bank]] (ADB) issued a publication summarizing the economic effects of the COVID-19 outbreak as a whole on the [[Developing country|developing countries]] in Asia, including the Philippines.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=Abiad|first=Abdul|url=https://www.adb.org/publications/economic-impact-covid19-developing-asia|title=The Economic Impact of the COVID-19 Outbreak on Developing Asia|last2=Arao|first2=Rosa Mia|last3=Dagli|first3=Suzette|date=March 6, 2020|publisher=Asian Development Bank|isbn=978-92-9262-063-9|language=en}}</ref> According to graphical representation presented by ADB in the publication, the GDP impact of the outbreak in the Philippines would be about between 0.0 to -0.5 percentage of the GDP in a best-case scenario while in a worst-case scenario, it would be around slightly near -0.5 percentage of the GDP with a hypothetical worst-case impact of about near -1.5 percentage of the GDP.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/publication/571536/adb-brief-128-economic-impact-covid19-developing-asia.pdf|title=The Economic Impact of the COVID-19 Outbreak on Developing Asia|last=|first=|date=March 6, 2020|website=Asian Development Bank|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The publication also indicated that tourism and business travel are the important channels through which economies will be affected in developing countries of Asia as well as supply-side disruptions and economic effects in other important channels through health and health care.<ref name=\":11\" /> In addition, ADB predicted that due to prolonged COVID-19 woes, there are at least 87,000 jobless Filipinos in a best-case scenario, while in a worst-case scenario, 252,000 Filipinos would lose their jobs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/business/2020/3/6/ADB-coronavirus-estimate-losses.html|title=PH job cuts may hit over 250,000 with prolonged coronavirus outbreak \u2013 ADB|last=Lopez|first=Melissa Luz|date=March 6, 2020|website=CNN Philippines|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Environmental ===\nData that were released on March 25, 2020 by the [[Department of Environment and Natural Resources]], the Institute of Environmental Science & Meteorology (IESM) at the [[University of the Philippines Diliman]], and Airtoday.ph indicate a better air quality in Metro Manila since the implementation of the Luzon enhanced community quarantine on March 16.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/25/20/look-data-show-less-polluted-air-in-metro-manila-amid-lockdown|title=LOOK: Data show less polluted air in Metro Manila amid lockdown|last=Sabillo|first=Kristine|date=March 25, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> PM2.5 (particulate matter 2.5 micrometers or less in diameter) was decreased to 180%.<ref name=\":14\" /> At the same time, [[Particulates|PM10]] (particulate matter 10 micrometers or less in diameter) emissions were reduced significantly due to lessened utilization of machines that crush and grind as well as low dust exposure from roads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/25/metro-manila-improves-air-quality-amid-quarantine.html|title=Metro Manila air quality improves during quarantine|last=|first=|date=March 25, 2020|website=CNN Philippines|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBecause of lowered air pollution during the Luzon lockdown, previously hazy skies can be seen clearly in Metro Manila. Some of the landscapes that are very visible in Metro Manila during the Luzon-wide lockdown include the [[Sierra Madre (Philippines)|Sierra Madre mountains]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/hashtag/content/731272/photos-of-rare-clear-view-of-sierra-madre-from-metro-manila-go-viral/story/|title=Photos of rare clear view of Sierra Madre from Metro Manila go viral|last=Bigtas|first=Jannielyn|date=March 25, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> and [[Mount Samat]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/hashtag/content/731455/mt-samat-shrine-in-bataan-seen-from-gma-network-building/story/|title=LOOK: Mt. Samat shrine in Bataan seen from GMA Network building|last=|first=|date=March 26, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> which rarely seen clearly due to smog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/27/20/look-these-photos-of-metro-manilas-skyline-show-how-air-quality-has-improved-since-lockdown|title=LOOK: These photos of Metro Manila's skyline show how air quality has improved since lockdown|last=Bagaoisan|first=Anjo|date=March 27, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Law and crime ===\nThe [[Commission on Human Rights (Philippines)|Commission on Human Rights]] (CHR) stated that arrests due to disobeying the enhanced community quarantine guidelines must be done in accordance with the law as the agency receives complaints regarding arrests.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/20/20/chr-issues-caution-on-arrests-amid-luzon-lockdown|title=CHR issues caution on arrests amid Luzon lockdown|date=March 20, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> CHR spokesperson Jacqueline Ann de Guia noted that all arrests, including [[Arrest warrant|warrantless arrests]], \"must be strictly done within the legal standards inscribed in the law.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> She also added that the Luzon quarantine is not [[Martial law in the Philippines|martial law]], which President Duterte also stressed, but a safety measure.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n[[Department of Justice (Philippines)|Department of Justice]] Secretary [[Menardo Guevarra]] earlier said that the arrests due to resisting and disobeying quarantine rules falls under [[List of Philippine laws|Republic Act]] 11332 (law on reporting of communicable diseases) as well as the [[Revised Penal Code of the Philippines]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/254788-doj-says-resisting-disobeying-basis-arrest-luzon-quarantine-coronavirus|title=In Luzon quarantine, DOJ says resisting and disobeying basis for arrest|last=Buan|first=Lian|date=March 17, 2020|website=Rappler|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2019/04/26/republic-act-no-11332/|title=Republic Act No. 11332 {{!}} GOVPH|date=July 23, 2018|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Although, former [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court]] spokesperson Ted Te opined that Republic Act 11332 is too broad to be a reason for the arrests.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn Metro Manila, it was reported that crime rates went down by 65.4% during the first five days of the enhanced community quarantine, from March 15 to 20, according to [[National Capital Region Police Office]] (NCRPO).<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730698/crime-down-by-more-than-60-with-enhanced-community-quarantine-ncrpo/story/|title=Crime down by more than 60% with enhanced community quarantine \u2014NCRPO|last=Santos|first=Jamil|date=March 21, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The reason for the decrease was attributed to people staying at their homes as stated by NCRPO chief Police Major General Debold Sinas.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Military diplomacy ===\nOne of the pronouncement made by President Duterte related to the Luzon-wide lockdown is implementing a ceasefire with the CPP-NPA ([[Communist Party of the Philippines]]-[[New People's Army]]) rebels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/16/duterte-covid-19-cpp-npa.html?fbclid=IwAR06a3uuPn8hqBBcomr56rhAKlaxivaoWp7_1VgHO1OOnVTfleMAsHmZqHM|title=Duterte asks communist rebels for ceasefire amid COVID-19 fight|last=Santos|first=Eimor|date=March 16, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> This is done for the forces of the state to focus its resources to stop the spread of the COVID-19.<ref name=\":9\" /> He also urged the rebels to help the government on their efforts against the COVID-19 threat.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/18/duterte-cpp-npa-ceasefire-covid-19.html|title=Duterte declares unilateral ceasefire with CPP-NPA to focus on COVID-19 fight|last=Santos|first=Eimor|date=March 18, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Jose Maria Sison]], CPP's founding chairman, initially said that the CPP and NDFP ([[National Democratic Front of the Philippines]]) will study the ceasefire offer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/17/2001576/sison-cpp-seriously-study-ceasefire-proposal-amid-covid-19-threat|title=Sison: CPP to 'seriously study' ceasefire proposal amid COVID-19 threat|last=Patag|first=Kristine Joy|date=March 17, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> He later responded and said that the NDFP \"is not assured and satisfied that the reciprocal unilateral ceasefires are based on national unity against COVID-19.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/20/20/joma-sison-palace-ceasefire-npa-coronavirus-crisis|title=Sison told: COVID-19 pandemic is your chance to prove you want peace|last=Merez|first=Arianne|date=March 20, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> \n\n=== Religious ===\nIn response to the prohibition of mass gatherings during the \"enhanced community quarantine\" throughout Luzon, the [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines]] (CBCP) through its [[President of the Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines|President]], Archbishop [[Romulo Valles]], said that the celebration of the [[Eucharist]], other liturgical services and spiritual activities from every diocese under their jurisdiction have to be broadcast live through the internet, television or radio.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bworldonline.com/virtual-religious-gatherings-amidst-covid-19/|title=Virtual religious gatherings amidst COVID-19|last=Soliman|first=Michelle Anne P.|date=March 18, 2020|website=bworldonline.com|publisher=[[BusinessWorld]] Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/09/20/mass-livestream-alcohol-at-church-entrances-as-manila-archdiocese-guards-against-covid-19|title=Mass livestream, alcohol at church entrances as Manila archdiocese guards against COVID-19|date=March 9, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> All activities for the [[Lent]]en season are also cancelled.<ref name=\":3\" /> Earlier during the Metro Manila partial lockdown, the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Manila|Archdiocese of Manila]] through its Apostolic Administrator, Bishop [[Broderick Pabillo]], already cancelled the celebration of the Holy Mass and dispensed the faithful from attending it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729504/malolos-diocese-encourage-public-to-watch-mass-on-tv-or-facebook-live/story/|title=No public mass for seven days in Manila archdiocese to help curb COVID-19|date=March 13, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther Christian churches such as a Baptist church in Quezon City also broadcast their religious service via [[live streaming]] amidst the COVID-19 threat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/photo/03/15/20/churches-turn-to-livestream-during-community-quarantine|title=Churches turn to livestream during community quarantine|last=Demayo,|first=Mark|date=March 15, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The spokesperson of the [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], Dean Jacek, said that they are also doing live streaming for their congregations.<ref name=\":3\" /> In different circumstances, the [[Iglesia ni Cristo]] announced the absence of worship services at their chapels.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730500/iglesia-ni-cristo-to-hold-no-worship-service-at-chapels-amid-covid-19-quarantine/story/|title=Iglesia ni Cristo to hold no worship service at chapels amid COVID-19 quarantine|date=March 19, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Instead, they advised their members to pray at home and they have given them lessons or guides that will be read by the head of the household.<ref name=\":4\" /> The [[Philippine Council of Evangelical Churches]] (PCEC), an organization composed of Evangelical and Protestant church member organizations, announced the suspension of regular Sunday worship services and other regular activities for a month and instead held its services via internet and social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/13/pcec-calls-for-cancellation-of-worship-services/|title=PCEC calls for cancellation of worship services|last=Aquino|first=Leslie Ann|date=March 13, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter consulting with the Ulama and Imam Association of the Philippines, and the Imam Council of the Philippines, the [[National Commission on Muslim Filipinos]] stated that religious activities are suspended and encouraged Filipino Muslims to pray and stay at home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/16/2001412/islamic-religious-activities-metro-manila-other-areas-under-covid-19-quarantine-temporarily-suspended|title=Islamic religious activities in Metro Manila, other areas under COVID-19 quarantine temporarily suspended|last=Cabico|first=Gaea Katreena|date=March 16, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729878/muslim-congregational-prayers-suspended-amid-ncr-community-quarantine/story/|title=Muslim congregational prayers suspended amid NCR community quarantine|last=Panti|first=Llanesca T.|date=March 16, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> This is done to limit the result of the COVID-19's continuous spread, given that people had died in a Muslim prayer hall in [[San Juan, Metro Manila]] due to COVID-19.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/downloads/2020/03mar/20200316-MEMORANDUM-FROM-ES-RRD.pdf Memorandum from Executive Security Salvador Medialdea regarding the guidelines on the Luzon enhanced community quaratine]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|Philippines]]\n[[Category:Country subdivisions lockdowns|Philippines]]\n[[Category:2020 in the Philippines|Luzon enhanced community quarantine]]\n[[Category:Containment efforts related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Quarantine in Luzon}}\n{{update|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current quarantine|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n|title=2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine\n|causes=[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]]\n|date={{start date|2020|03|17|mf=y}}\u2013{{abbr|present|assuming that it does not get lifted early or extended, April 2020 is the expiry date}} (scheduled to expire on {{end date|2020|04|12|mf=y}})\n|image=\n|caption=\n|place=[[Luzon]], [[Philippines]] including its associated islands\n|side3=\n|side2=\n|side1=\n|result=About 57 million people quarantined (all of Luzon)<ref name=\"aljazeera\"/>\n|methods=Checkpoints for checking the motivation for travels, banning of public events, closure of commercial and retail businesses, closure of schools and universities until April 12 and other prohibitions.\n|goals=To contain the outbreak of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in the Philippines\n}}\n\nOn March 16, 2020, [[Rodrigo Duterte]] declared the entire [[Luzon]] area in the Philippines under \"enhanced community [[quarantine]],\" which is effectively a total [[lockdown]], restricting the movement of the population with exceptions, in response to the growing [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|pandemic]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in the country. Additional lockdown restrictions mandated the temporary closure of non-essential shops and businesses. This quarantine came two days after the implementation of the community quarantine of [[Metro Manila]]. The quarantine is expected to last until April 2020.\n\n== Background ==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\nFollowing the outbreak of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) which started in [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China, the Philippine government confirmed the country's first case of the disease on January 30, 2020, when the virus was detected in a Chinese national who traveled from Wuhan, China and Hong Kong.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/30/20/philippines-confirms-first-case-of-new-coronavirus|title=Philippines confirms first case of new coronavirus|date=January 30, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref> The second case was confirmed on February 2, with the patient being the husband of the first case who was also Chinese.<ref name=\":01\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/first-coronavirus-death-outside-china-reported-philippines-n1128371|title=First coronavirus death outside China reported in Philippines|date=February 2, 2020|publisher=NBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> Three days later, on February 5, another Chinese national was confirmed to the be third case in the Philippines.<ref name=\"doh3rd\">{{cite web|url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/doh-press-release/doh-confirms-3rd-2019-nCoV-ARD-case-in-PH|title=DOH confirms 3rd 2019-nCoV ARD Case iN PH|date=February 5, 2020|website=Department of Health (Philippines)|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205081612/https://www.doh.gov.ph/doh-press-release/doh-confirms-3rd-2019-nCoV-ARD-case-in-PH|archive-date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> After a month, on March 5, the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] announced that the first Filipino in the Philippines confirmed to be infected with COVID-19 who is also the fourth case while the fifth case is the first case of local transmission since the infected person did not travel outside the Philippines.<ref name=\"DOHNC2\">{{cite news|last1=Punzalan|first1=Jamaine|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/06/20/new-coronavirus-case-in-philippines-possible-local-transmission|title=Philippines' new coronavirus cases now at 5, including potential local transmission|date=March 6, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>[https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1238159/doh-deloitte-ph-employee-is-4th-coronavirus-case-5th-case-is-from-cainta DOH : Deloitte PH employee is 4th coronavirus case; 5th case is from Cainta | Inquirer News]</ref> The sixth case that was confirmed on March 7 is the wife of the fifth case.<ref name=\"codered\">{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/07/20/code-red-philippines-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-6-doh-confirms-local-transmission|title=CODE RED: Philippines' coronavirus cases rise to 6, DOH confirms local transmission|date=March 7, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> In the following days, the number of cases steadily increased.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/253882-new-philippines-novel-coronavirus-cases-march-9-2020|title=Novel coronavirus cases in Philippines spike to 20}}</ref>\n\n== Lockdowns ==\n=== Initial lockdowns ===\n[[File:PNP PRO 3 Checkpoints COVID 19 2.jpg|thumb|Police checkpoint near the border of [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila]] with [[Meycauayan]], [[Bulacan]].]]\nOn March 8, 2020, President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] signed Proclamation 922 placing the entire Philippines under state of public health emergency because of the COVID-19 threat that is looming in the nation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/downloads/2020/02feb/20200308-PROC-922-RRD-1.pdf|title=Proclamation No. 922|date=March 8, 2020|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On the next day, March 9, [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Congressman]] Joey Salceda of the [[Legislative districts of Albay#2nd District|2nd district of the province of Albay]] recommended a [[lockdown]] of the entire [[National Capital Region]] (NCR) for a period of seven days, in response to the COVID-19 threat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728901/lawmaker-wants-weeklong-ncr-lockdown-to-prevent-spread-of-covid-19/story/|title=Lawmaker wants weeklong NCR lockdown amid COVID-19 threat|date=March 9, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Some of his proposals for implementing the lockdown include banning mass transportation and stopping the operation of the [[Philippine expressway network]] that ply to and from the region, and cancelling of classes and work.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Panti|first1=Llanesca|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728901/lawmaker-wants-weeklong-ncr-lockdown-to-prevent-spread-of-covid-19/story/|title=Lawmaker wants weeklong NCR lockdown amid COVID-19 threat|date=March 9, 2020|work=GMA News Online|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> At first, President Rodrigo Duterte turned down the idea because it would \"hamper the flow of basic commodities,\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lopez|first1=Virgil|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729000/duterte-thumbs-down-lockdown-for-metro-manila-over-covid-19/story/?just_in|title=Duterte thumbs down lockdown for Metro Manila over COVID-19|date=March 9, 2020|work=GMA News Online|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> although, Health Secretary [[Francisco Duque]] III, opined that the lockdown may put into effect in some areas where there are reported community-based transmissions, but not the whole NCR.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.ph/news/2020/3/10/Philippines-lockdown-coronavirus.html|title=DOH: 'Localized lockdown' possible amid coronavirus pandemic|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 10, 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nPresident Duterte announced on March 12, 2020 the \"community quarantine\" on [[Metro Manila]] starting at 12 midnight on March 15 up to April 14 that will cover 16 cities and one municipality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/254101-metro-manila-placed-on-lockdown-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Metro Manila to be placed on lockdown due to coronavirus outbreak|last=Talabong|first=Rambo|date=March 12, 2020|website=Rappler|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Traveling through land, domestic air, and domestic sea from Metro Manila was suspended with exceptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/254361-questions-filipinos-metro-manila-coronavirus-lockdown|title=Questions Filipinos are asking about the coronavirus lockdown|last=Baizas|first=Gaby|date=March 13, 2020|website=Rappler|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> For international travel, restrictions are imposed on those who came from countries with localized COVID-19 transmissions, except for citizens of the Philippines (including their foreign spouse and children) or holders of permanent resident visas and diplomat visas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/12/duterte-expands-ban-on-travelers-from-countries-with-local-covid-19-transmissions|title=Duterte expands ban on travelers from countries with local COVID-19 transmissions|last=Geducos|first=Argyll|date=March 13, 2020|website=Manila Bulletin News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Mass transportation vehicles are allowed to operate provided that persons riding these vehicles comply with the social distancing guidelines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/pnp-metro-manila-lockdown.html|title=PNP to man checkpoints in Metro Manila 'lockdown'|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Curfew]] has also put into place by the local government units of Metro Manila.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/15/Coronavirus-COVID-19-updates.html|title=LIVE UPDATES: Metro Manila community quarantine takes effect amid COVID-19 outbreak|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Expansion to Luzon ===\n[[File:COVID-19 Community Quarantine Checkpoint in Cagayan.jpg|thumb|A police-manned checkpoint in [[Tuguegarao]].]]\n[[File:Philippine Red Cross thermal scanning COVID19 Bayombong.jpg|thumb|[[Philippine Red Cross]] volunteers scanning the temperature of commuters entering the provincial capitol in [[Bayombong]], [[Nueva Vizcaya]].]]\nDuring the second day of the implementation of the Metro Manila community quarantine, on March 16, President Duterte declared a Luzon-wide \"enhanced community quarantine\" that aims to further combat the effect of the continuing and increasing spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/iq/254783-full-text-guidelines-luzon-enhanced-community-quarantine|title=GUIDELINES: Luzon 'enhanced community quarantine'|date=March 16, 2020|website=Rappler.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729875/duterte-orders-lockdown-of-entire-luzon-due-to-covid-19-threat/story/|title=COVID-19 THREAT: Duterte orders Luzon-wide 'enhanced community quarantine'|date=March 16, 2020|website=[[GMA News Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> It took effect on March 17 and will end on April 12.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/16/entire-luzon-under-quarantine|title=Entire Luzon under quarantine|last=Geducos|first=Argyll Cyrus|date=March 16, 2020|website=[[Manila Bulletin]] News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1096849|title=Mass transport suspended under enhanced community quarantine|last=Parrocha|first=Azer|last2=Dela Cruz|first2=Raymond Carl|date=March 17, 2020|website=pna.gov.ph|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> This quarantine also applies to the [[Mimaropa|region of Mimaropa]] ([[Mindoro]], [[Marinduque]], [[Romblon]] and [[Palawan]]), which is outside the Luzon island.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://politics.com.ph/coronavirus-lockdown-covers-mimaropa-says-nograles/|title=Coronavirus lockdown covers MIMAROPA, says Nograles|date=March 17, 2020|work=Politko|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Under this new setup, mass gatherings are completely prohibited and all means of public transport is no longer allowed limiting the movement of people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730095/enhanced-community-quarantine-means-lockdown-in-luzon-says-ano/story/|title=Enhanced community quarantine means lockdown in Luzon, says A\u00f1o|last=Bajo|first=Anna Felicia|date=March 17, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Restrictions on the people's movement ====\nAll schools in all levels are temporarily prohibited to conduct classes and activities until April 14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/downloads/2020/03mar/20200316-MEMORANDUM-FROM-ES-RRD.pdf|title=COMMUNITY QUARANTINE OVER THE ENTIRE LUZON AND GUIDELINES FOR THE MANAGEMENT OF THE CORONAVIRUS DISEASE 2019 (COVID-19) SITUATION|last=Medialdea|first=Salvador C.|authorlink=Salvador Medialdea|date=March 16, 2020|website=[[Official Gazette (Philippines)|Official Gazette of the government of the Republic of the Philippines]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=March 20, 2020|access-date=}}</ref> A \"[[Telecommuting|work from home]]\" scheme is applied to the government workers of the [[Executive departments of the Philippines|executive branch]] except for the skeletal workforce consisting of uniformed personnel ([[Philippine National Police]], [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]], and [[Philippine Coast Guard]]), those providing services in the frontline of health and emergency, and border control.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243433/csc-on-work-from-home-arrangement|title=CSC: Work from home scheme for gov\u2019t workers until Luzon quarantine is lifted|last=Ramos|first=Christia Marie|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> For the private sector, companies are also advised to implement a \"work from home\" arrangement.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/luzon-quarantine-a-breakdown-of-the-implementing-guidelines|title=Luzon quarantine: A breakdown of the implementing guidelines|last=Merez|first=Arianne|date=March 17, 2020|website=[[ABS-CBN News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe populace's movement is restricted to their homes and they can only go outside to just buy basic needs such as food, medicines and other things needed for sustenance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/coronavirus-massive-cracks-in-manila-lockdown-luzon-under-enhanced-community-quarantine|title=Coronavirus: Duterte places a third of the Philippines on sweeping lockdown|last=Dancel|first=Raul|date=March 16, 2020|website=[[The Straits Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Only a single person per household can go outside to buy basic necessities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/only-one-person-per-family-allowed-to-leave-house-manila-city-government|title=Only one person per family allowed to leave house \u2013 Manila city government|last=Tiangco|first=Minka|date=March 18, 2020|website=Manila Bulletin News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> In particular, the [[Manila|City of Manila]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/photo/315512/home-quarantine-pass-allows-one-per-household-in-manila-to-go-out-for-supplies/photo/|title=Home quarantine pass allows one per household in Manila to go out for supplies|last=Panganiban-Perez|first=Tina|date=March 19, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> [[Bacoor]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/19/20/bacoor-lockdown-checkpoints-sa-boundaries-quarantine-pass-sa-kada-pamilya|title=Bacoor lockdown: Checkpoints sa boundaries, quarantine pass sa kada pamilya|date=March 19, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|language=tl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> and other places<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1244557/in-bicol-villages-pieces-of-paper-called-quarantine-passes-required-for-residents-leaving-homes|title=In Bicol villages, pieces of paper called \u2018quarantine passes\u2019 required for residents leaving homes|last=Mier-Manjares|first=Ma April|date=March 18, 2020|website=Philippine Daily Inquirer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> issued quarantine passes to persons who were designated by their household would go out their homes to buy needed goods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036629|title=Agoo town to impose \u2018quarantine pass\u2019 to thwart COVID-19 spread|last=Dilim|first=Joanne Namnama P.|date=March 19, 2020|website=pia.gov.ph|publisher=[[Philippine Information Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The \"enhanced community quarantine\" also directs stricter [[social distancing]] protocols where people going to public places must observe one meter distance apart from each other. In connection to this, businesses who provide food and medicine are allowed to operate.<ref name=\"aljazeera\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-philippines-quarantines-island-57-million-people-200316161225532.html|title=Coronavirus: Philippines quarantines island of 57 million people|last=Santos|first=Ana P.|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=Al Jazeera|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Closure of establishments ====\nFurthermore, financial institutions such as bank and money transfer services and utility providers are also not barred to open. Capital markets such as the [[Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas]], the [[Securities and Exchange Commission (Philippines)|Securities and Exchange Commission]], and the [[Philippine Stock Exchange]], were permitted to open only on March 18, provided that skeletal workforce are set up.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/18/2001644/stock-trading-resumes-tomorrow|title=Stock trading resumes tomorrow|last=Gonzales|first=Iris|date=March 18, 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Those industries who act as [[Business process outsourcing in the Philippines|Business Process Outsourcing]] or [[Call center industry in the Philippines|call centers]] as well as export-oriented industries are also allowed to continue with their operations as long as they observe social distancing protocols, temporary shelter for their employees by March 18, and keep up with a skeletal workforce.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Barcelo|first=Vito|url=https://manilastandard.net/news/top-stories/319845/duterte-puts-entire-luzon-on-lockdown.html|title=Duterte puts entire Luzon on lockdown|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[Manila Standard]]|access-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live|last2=Zurbano|first2=Joel|last3=Ramos-Araneta|first3=Macon}}</ref> Hotels and other businesses that provide accommodation are not operational and they are only allowed to lodge foreign guests who have bookings or guests who have long-term leases as of March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/254943-hotel-bookings-banned-coronavirus-lockdown|title=No new hotel bookings during coronavirus lockdown|last=Gotinga|first=J. C.|date=March 18, 2020|website=Rappler|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Travel restrictions ====\n[[File:SM North EDSA Terminal COVID-19 quarantine.jpg|thumb|The usually-filled public transport terminal at the SM North EDSA devoid of any vehicle due to the quarantine measures.]]\nTraveling through air, sea and land is restricted only to diplomats, uniformed workers (especially those who travel with medical supplies, specimens from the laboratory in relation to COVID-19), and those who do humanitarian work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/16/second-headline/look-memorandum-on-enhanced-quarantine/703697/|title=LOOK: Memorandum on enhanced quarantine|date=March 16, 2020|website=[[The Manila Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> People who are going outside the Philippines through Luzon are only limited to [[Overseas Filipino Worker]]s and foreigners;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/19/20/ph-eyes-suspension-of-visa-issuance-amid-covid-19-lockdown|title=PH eyes suspension of visa issuance amid COVID-19 lockdown|date=March 19, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> and they must be escorted by only one person.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/govt-amends-travel-restrictions-travelers-may-leave-through-any-luzon-port-with-conditions|title=Gov't amends travel restrictions; travelers may leave through any Luzon port with conditions|last=Kabiling|first=Genalyn|date=March 18, 2020|website=Manila Bulletin News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the other hand, only [[Philippine nationality law|Filipino citizens]] and diplomats with visas issued by the government of the Philippines are the ones who have permission to enter the Philippines through international airports in Luzon provided that they undergo quarantine procedures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/255000-government-maintains-all-filipinos-abroad-can-return-philippines-despite-luzon-lockdown|title=Filipinos abroad can return to PH despite Luzon lockdown|last=Tomacruz|first=Sofia|date=March 18, 2020|website=Rappler|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> International travelers in transit are also allowed to enter but subject to quarantine procedures too.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/17/c_138887115.htm|title=Philippines to shut down all airports in Luzon starting Friday to curb COVID-19 spread \u2013 Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|date=n.d.|agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Foreigners who wish to come to the Philippines can go through Cebu but they must go undergo quarantine procedures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245312/ph-barring-foreigners-dfa-says-no-exceptions?utm_source=izooto&utm_medium=push_notifications&utm_campaign=PHbarringforeignersDFAsaysnoexceptions&utm_content=&utm_term=|title=PH barring foreigners; DFA says no exceptions|last=Pazzibugan|first=Dona Z.|date=March 16, 2020|website=Philippine Daily Inquirer|publisher=Cebu Daily News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> However, this was changed when [[Department of Foreign Affairs (Philippines)|Department of Foreign Affairs]] (DFA) Secretary [[Teodoro Locsin Jr.|Teodoro Locsin Jr]]. announced on March 19 the suspension of visas and visa-free privileges of foreigners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/19/Philippines-DFA-considering-visa-issuance-suspension-Locsin-coronavirus-COVID.html|title=Philippines suspends visa issuance as worldwide COVID-19 cases soar \u2013 Locsin|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Although, DFA clarified on March 20 that there are exceptions.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/20/DFA-visa-issuance-suspension-wont-affect-foreigners-in-PH.html|title=Foreigners already in PH won't be forced to leave despite visa suspension policy, DFA clarifies|date=March 20, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Foreigners who are in the Philippines already or whose visas issued by other government agencies can stay until they depart from the Philippines.<ref name=\":2\" /> In addition, visas is still valid for foreigners who have Filipino spouses or foreigners who have Filipino parents.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nCargo forwarders, farmers, and other food producers are not covered by the travel prohibition but they must go through quarantine checkpoints.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.panaynews.net/farmers-exempted-from-travel-restrictions-during-quarantine-period/|title=Farmers exempted from travel restrictions during quarantine period|date=March 18, 2020|website=Panay News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Those who are guarding or securing an establishment are only permitted to work and travel within the area of their responsibility.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/world/1880700/confusion-as-locked-down-philippines-starts-virus-quarantine|title=Confusion as locked-down Philippines starts virus quarantine|last=Limited|first=Bangkok Post Public Company|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Media practitioners with their vehicles are allowed to go to the quarantine area as long as they get a media pass from the [[Presidential Communications Group (Philippines)|Presidential Communications Operations Office]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1244893/media-personnel-still-allowed-to-travel-cover-during-enhanced-community-quarantine|title=No quarantine period coverage restrictions for duly accredited media personnel|last=Aguilar|first=Krissy|date=March 19, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Terminology ===\n{{See also|Lockdown|Quarantine}}At one point during President Duterte's pronouncement about the Metro Manila \"community quarantine,\" he said that \"they are afraid to call it a lockdown, but it is a lockdown.\"<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Coronavirus/Duterte-orders-Manila-lockdown-from-Sunday|title=Duterte orders Manila lockdown from Sunday|last=Venzon|first=Cliff|date=March 13, 2020|website=[[Nikkei Asian Review]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Petty|first=Martin|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-philippines-casual-idUSKBN20Z2BV|title=Philippine capital on lockdown to contain coronavirus|date=March 12, 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live|last2=Lema|first2=Karen|language=en}}</ref> This statement left many confused.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1096510|title=No lockdown, just 'community quarantine': Nograles|last=Cudis|first=Christine|date=March 13, 2020|website=www.pna.gov.ph|publisher=[[Philippine News Agency]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> His [[Cabinet Secretariat of the Philippines|cabinet secretary]], [[Karlo Nograles]], later made it clear that the proper term is \"community quarantine\" and the President's comment means that the event \"is like a lockdown.\"<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":16\" /> Nograles further said that the term \"lockdown\" can be understood by different interpretations while \"community quarantine\" is a technical term that medical authorities can give meaning and it does not create public fear.<ref name=\":16\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/13/2000574/is-it-lockdown-or-community-quarantine-your-questions-about-latest-move-vs-covid-19-answered|title='Is it a lockdown or a community quarantine?' Your questions about latest move vs COVID-19 answered|last=Cabico|first=Gaea Katreena|date=March 13, 2020|website=philstar.com|publisher=The Philippine Star|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\nWhen the \"community quarantine\" was applied to Luzon, [[Presidential Communications Group (Philippines)#Presidential Spokesperson|Presidential Spokeperson]] [[Salvador Panelo]], said that the Luzon-wide \"enhanced community quarantine\" is equivalent to an \"absolute lockdown or total lockdown.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/16/20/duterte-places-luzon-under-enhanced-community-quarantine-to-fight-covid-19|title=Luzon under enhanced community quarantine as COVID-19 cases rise|last=Merez|first=Arianne|date=March 16, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Secretary [[Eduardo A\u00f1o]] of the [[Department of the Interior and Local Government|Department of Interior and Local Government]] also said that \"enhanced community quarantine\" should be considered as a \"total lockdown.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730095/enhanced-community-quarantine-means-lockdown-in-luzon-says-ano/story/|title=Enhanced community quarantine means lockdown in Luzon, says A\u00f1o|last=Bajo|first=Anna Felicia|date=March 17, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Impact and reactions ==\n\n=== Economic ===\nCongressman Joey Salceda who is the House of the Representatives Committee Chairman on Ways and Means said that the Philippines could go into [[recession]] if there is no implementation of a community quarantine, although, he admitted that the  COVID-19 pandemic will affect the [[economy of the Philippines]] in a negative way.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/economy/730787/philippines-could-sink-into-recession-without-community-quarantine/story/|title=Philippines could sink into recession without community quarantine, says Salceda|last=Colcol|first=Erwin|date=March 22, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> According to Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas (BSP) Governor [[Benjamin Diokno]] on March 18, 2020, the economic impact is still not known but \"it will definitely have an impact.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1096999|title=Luzon-wide quarantine to benefit people, economy|last=Villanueva|first=Joann|date=March 18, 2020|website=pna.gov.ph|agency=[[Philippine News Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Two days later, on March 20, 2020, the BSP said that the shutdown of Luzon will slow down the economy of the Philippines with a disruptive impact.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/business/2020/3/20/coronavirus-PH-economy.html|title=COVID-19 to weigh down economic growth for the rest of 2020|last=|first=|date=March 20, 2020|website=CNN Philippines|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> BSP further said the economic impact would last until the second half of 2020 but it is expected to rebound on 2021.<ref name=\":12\" /> \n\nIn other forecast, the domestic output estimates by economic managers for the year 2020 are from 0.3 to 1.0 percentage point.<ref name=\":0\" /> The [[National Economic and Development Authority]] revised its 2020 economic growth forecast to 5.5 to 6.5 percent against the targeted 6.5 to 7.5 percent growth, assuming that the COVID-19 problem lasts until June 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/business/2020/3/9/NEDA-growth-forecast-coronavirus.html|title=NEDA lowers PH growth forecast amid coronavirus outbreak|last=|first=|date=March 9, 2020|website=CNN Philippines|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It is expected that the prices of basic goods will go up to 2.2 percent only compared to 2.5 percent average in 2019.<ref name=\":12\" />  [[Nomura Holdings|Nomura]], a [[Japan|Japanese]] financial [[holding company]], lowered its [[gross domestic product]] (GDP) estimates to the Philippines from 5.6% to 1.6%.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/30/2004400/covid-19-luzon-lockdown-seen-pull-gdp-growth-down-lowest-level-2009|title=COVID-19, Luzon lockdown seen to pull GDP growth down to lowest level since 2009|last=Cigaral|first=Ian Nicolas|date=March 30, 2020|website=philstar.com|publisher=The Philippine Star|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The analysts from the holding company further said that the estimates assume a scenario where the Luzon lockdown ends on the middle of April as scheduled.<ref name=\":13\" /> After the two-day closure of the Philippine Stock Exchange due the Luzon lockdown, the market crashed to about 24 percent reaching the 4,000 level, which is an eight-year low.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nOn March 6, 2020, the [[Asian Development Bank]] (ADB) issued a publication summarizing the economic effects of the COVID-19 outbreak as a whole on the [[Developing country|developing countries]] in Asia, including the Philippines.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=Abiad|first=Abdul|url=https://www.adb.org/publications/economic-impact-covid19-developing-asia|title=The Economic Impact of the COVID-19 Outbreak on Developing Asia|last2=Arao|first2=Rosa Mia|last3=Dagli|first3=Suzette|date=2020-03-06|publisher=Asian Development Bank|isbn=978-92-9262-063-9|language=en}}</ref> According to graphical representation presented by ADB in the publication, the GDP impact of the outbreak in the Philippines would be about between 0.0 to -0.5 percentage of the GDP in a best-case scenario while in a worst-case scenario, it would be around slightly near -0.5 percentage of the GDP with a hypothetical worst-case impact of about near -1.5 percentage of the GDP.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/publication/571536/adb-brief-128-economic-impact-covid19-developing-asia.pdf|title=The Economic Impact of the COVID-19 Outbreak on Developing Asia|last=|first=|date=March 6, 2020|website=Asian Development Bank|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The publication also indicated that tourism and business travel are the important channels through which economies will be affected in developing countries of Asia as well as supply-side disruptions and economic effects in other important channels through health and health care.<ref name=\":11\" /> In addition, ADB predicted that due to prolonged COVID-19 woes, there are at least 87,000 jobless Filipinos in a best-case scenario, while in a worst-case scenario, 252,000 Filipinos would lose their jobs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/business/2020/3/6/ADB-coronavirus-estimate-losses.html|title=PH job cuts may hit over 250,000 with prolonged coronavirus outbreak \u2013 ADB|last=Lopez|first=Melissa Luz|date=March 6, 2020|website=CNN Philippines|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Environmental ===\nData that were released on March 25, 2020 by the [[Department of Environment and Natural Resources]], the Institute of Environmental Science & Meteorology (IESM) at the [[University of the Philippines Diliman]], and Airtoday.ph indicate a better air quality in Metro Manila since the implementation of the Luzon enhanced community quarantine on March 16.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/25/20/look-data-show-less-polluted-air-in-metro-manila-amid-lockdown|title=LOOK: Data show less polluted air in Metro Manila amid lockdown|last=Sabillo|first=Kristine|date=March 25, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> PM2.5 (particulate matter 2.5 micrometers or less in diameter) was decreased to 180%.<ref name=\":14\" /> At the same time, [[Particulates|PM10]] (particulate matter 10 micrometers or less in diameter) emissions were reduced significantly due to lessened utilization of machines that crush and grind as well as low dust exposure from roads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/25/metro-manila-improves-air-quality-amid-quarantine.html|title=Metro Manila air quality improves during quarantine|last=|first=|date=March 25, 2020|website=CNN Philippines|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBecause of lowered air pollution during the Luzon lockdown, previously hazy skies can be seen clearly in Metro Manila. Some of the landscapes that are very visible in Metro Manila during the Luzon-wide lockdown include the [[Sierra Madre (Philippines)|Sierra Madre mountains]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/hashtag/content/731272/photos-of-rare-clear-view-of-sierra-madre-from-metro-manila-go-viral/story/|title=Photos of rare clear view of Sierra Madre from Metro Manila go viral|last=Bigtas|first=Jannielyn|date=March 25, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> and [[Mount Samat]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/hashtag/content/731455/mt-samat-shrine-in-bataan-seen-from-gma-network-building/story/|title=LOOK: Mt. Samat shrine in Bataan seen from GMA Network building|last=|first=|date=March 26, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> which rarely seen clearly due to smog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/27/20/look-these-photos-of-metro-manilas-skyline-show-how-air-quality-has-improved-since-lockdown|title=LOOK: These photos of Metro Manila's skyline show how air quality has improved since lockdown|last=Bagaoisan|first=Anjo|date=March 27, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Law and crime ===\nThe [[Commission on Human Rights (Philippines)|Commission on Human Rights]] (CHR) stated that arrests due to disobeying the enhanced community quarantine guidelines must be done in accordance with the law as the agency receives complaints regarding arrests.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/20/20/chr-issues-caution-on-arrests-amid-luzon-lockdown|title=CHR issues caution on arrests amid Luzon lockdown|date=March 20, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> CHR spokesperson Jacqueline Ann de Guia noted that all arrests, including [[Arrest warrant|warrantless arrests]], \"must be strictly done within the legal standards inscribed in the law.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> She also added that the Luzon quarantine is not [[Martial law in the Philippines|martial law]], which President Duterte also stressed, but a safety measure.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n[[Department of Justice (Philippines)|Department of Justice]] Secretary [[Menardo Guevarra]] earlier said that the arrests due to resisting and disobeying quarantine rules falls under [[List of Philippine laws|Republic Act]] 11332 (law on reporting of communicable diseases) as well as the [[Revised Penal Code of the Philippines]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/254788-doj-says-resisting-disobeying-basis-arrest-luzon-quarantine-coronavirus|title=In Luzon quarantine, DOJ says resisting and disobeying basis for arrest|last=Buan|first=Lian|date=March 17, 2020|website=Rappler|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2019/04/26/republic-act-no-11332/|title=Republic Act No. 11332 {{!}} GOVPH|date=July 23, 2018|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Although, former [[Supreme Court of the Philippines|Supreme Court]] spokesperson Ted Te opined that Republic Act 11332 is too broad to be a reason for the arrests.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn Metro Manila, it was reported that crime rates went down by 65.4% during the first five days of the enhanced community quarantine, from March 15 to 20, according to [[National Capital Region Police Office]] (NCRPO).<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730698/crime-down-by-more-than-60-with-enhanced-community-quarantine-ncrpo/story/|title=Crime down by more than 60% with enhanced community quarantine \u2014NCRPO|last=Santos|first=Jamil|date=March 21, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The reason for the decrease was attributed to people staying at their homes as stated by NCRPO chief Police Major General Debold Sinas.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Military diplomacy ===\nOne of the pronouncement made by President Duterte related to the Luzon-wide lockdown is implementing a ceasefire with the CPP-NPA ([[Communist Party of the Philippines]]-[[New People's Army]]) rebels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/16/duterte-covid-19-cpp-npa.html?fbclid=IwAR06a3uuPn8hqBBcomr56rhAKlaxivaoWp7_1VgHO1OOnVTfleMAsHmZqHM|title=Duterte asks communist rebels for ceasefire amid COVID-19 fight|last=Santos|first=Eimor|date=March 16, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> This is done for the forces of the state to focus its resources to stop the spread of the COVID-19.<ref name=\":9\" /> He also urged the rebels to help the government on their efforts against the COVID-19 threat.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/18/duterte-cpp-npa-ceasefire-covid-19.html|title=Duterte declares unilateral ceasefire with CPP-NPA to focus on COVID-19 fight|last=Santos|first=Eimor|date=March 18, 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Jose Maria Sison]], CPP's founding chairman, initially said that the CPP and NDFP ([[National Democratic Front of the Philippines]]) will study the ceasefire offer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/17/2001576/sison-cpp-seriously-study-ceasefire-proposal-amid-covid-19-threat|title=Sison: CPP to 'seriously study' ceasefire proposal amid COVID-19 threat|last=Patag|first=Kristine Joy|date=March 17, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> He later responded and said that the NDFP \"is not assured and satisfied that the reciprocal unilateral ceasefires are based on national unity against COVID-19.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/20/20/joma-sison-palace-ceasefire-npa-coronavirus-crisis|title=Sison told: COVID-19 pandemic is your chance to prove you want peace|last=Merez|first=Arianne|date=March 20, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> \n\n=== Religious ===\nIn response to the prohibition of mass gatherings during the \"enhanced community quarantine\" throughout Luzon, the [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines]] (CBCP) through its [[President of the Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines|President]], Archbishop [[Romulo Valles]], said that the celebration of the [[Eucharist]], other liturgical services and spiritual activities from every diocese under their jurisdiction have to be broadcast live through the internet, television or radio.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bworldonline.com/virtual-religious-gatherings-amidst-covid-19/|title=Virtual religious gatherings amidst COVID-19|last=Soliman|first=Michelle Anne P.|date=March 18, 2020|website=bworldonline.com|publisher=[[BusinessWorld]] Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/09/20/mass-livestream-alcohol-at-church-entrances-as-manila-archdiocese-guards-against-covid-19|title=Mass livestream, alcohol at church entrances as Manila archdiocese guards against COVID-19|date=March 9, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> All activities for the [[Lent]]en season are also cancelled.<ref name=\":3\" /> Earlier during the Metro Manila partial lockdown, the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Manila|Archdiocese of Manila]] through its Apostolic Administrator, Bishop [[Broderick Pabillo]], already cancelled the celebration of the Holy Mass and dispensed the faithful from attending it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729504/malolos-diocese-encourage-public-to-watch-mass-on-tv-or-facebook-live/story/|title=No public mass for seven days in Manila archdiocese to help curb COVID-19|date=March 13, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther Christian churches such as a Baptist church in Quezon City also broadcast their religious service via [[live streaming]] amidst the COVID-19 threat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/photo/03/15/20/churches-turn-to-livestream-during-community-quarantine|title=Churches turn to livestream during community quarantine|last=Demayo,|first=Mark|date=March 15, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The spokesperson of the [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], Dean Jacek, said that they are also doing live streaming for their congregations.<ref name=\":3\" /> In different circumstances, the [[Iglesia ni Cristo]] announced the absence of worship services at their chapels.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730500/iglesia-ni-cristo-to-hold-no-worship-service-at-chapels-amid-covid-19-quarantine/story/|title=Iglesia ni Cristo to hold no worship service at chapels amid COVID-19 quarantine|date=March 19, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> Instead, they advised their members to pray at home and they have given them lessons or guides that will be read by the head of the household.<ref name=\":4\" /> The [[Philippine Council of Evangelical Churches]] (PCEC), an organization composed of Evangelical and Protestant church member organizations, announced the suspension of regular Sunday worship services and other regular activities for a month and instead held its services via internet and social media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/13/pcec-calls-for-cancellation-of-worship-services/|title=PCEC calls for cancellation of worship services|last=Aquino|first=Leslie Ann|date=March 13, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter consulting with the Ulama and Imam Association of the Philippines, and the Imam Council of the Philippines, the [[National Commission on Muslim Filipinos]] stated that religious activities are suspended and encouraged Filipino Muslims to pray and stay at home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/16/2001412/islamic-religious-activities-metro-manila-other-areas-under-covid-19-quarantine-temporarily-suspended|title=Islamic religious activities in Metro Manila, other areas under COVID-19 quarantine temporarily suspended|last=Cabico|first=Gaea Katreena|date=March 16, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729878/muslim-congregational-prayers-suspended-amid-ncr-community-quarantine/story/|title=Muslim congregational prayers suspended amid NCR community quarantine|last=Panti|first=Llanesca T.|date=March 16, 2020|website=GMA News Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> This is done to limit the result of the COVID-19's continuous spread, given that people had died in a Muslim prayer hall in [[San Juan, Metro Manila]] due to COVID-19.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/downloads/2020/03mar/20200316-MEMORANDUM-FROM-ES-RRD.pdf Memorandum from Executive Security Salvador Medialdea regarding the guidelines on the Luzon enhanced community quaratine]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|Philippines]]\n[[Category:Country subdivisions lockdowns|Philippines]]\n[[Category:2020 in the Philippines|Luzon enhanced community quarantine]]\n[[Category:Containment efforts related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "HueMan1", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Luzon_enhanced_community_quarantine"}
